# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ken-burns
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The **14th Dalai Lama** (born **Lhamo Thondup**; 6 July 1935; full spiritual name: **Jetsun Jamphel Ngawang Lobsang Yeshe Tenzin Gyatso**, shortened as **Tenzin Gyatso**) is the incumbent Dalai Lama, the highest spiritual leader and head of Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He served as the resident spiritual and temporal leader of Tibet before 1959, and subsequently led the Tibetan government in exile represented by the Central Tibetan Administration in Dharamshala, India.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] A belief central to the Tibetan Buddhist tradition as well as the institution of the Dalai Lama is that the reincarnated person is a living Bodhisattva, specifically an emanation of Avalokiteśvara (in Sanskrit) or Chenrezig (in Tibetan), the Bodhisattva of Compassion.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Mongolic word *dalai* means *ocean.* The 14th Dalai Lama is also known to Tibetans as **Gyalwa Rinpoche** ("The Precious Jewel-like Buddha-Master"), *Kundun* ("The Presence"), and *Yizhin Norbu* ("The Wish-Fulfilling Gem").
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His devotees, as well as much of the Western world, often call him ***His Holiness the Dalai Lama***.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He is the leader and a monk of the newest Gelug school of Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 14th Dalai Lama was born to a farming family in Taktser (*Hongya* village), in the traditional Tibetan region of Amdo, at the time a Chinese frontier district.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He was selected as the tulku of the 13th Dalai Lama in 1937, and formally recognised as the 14th Dalai Lama in 1939.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] As with the recognition process for his predecessor, a Golden Urn selection process was waived and approved by the Nationalist government of China.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His enthronement ceremony was held in Lhasa on 22 February 1940.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Following the Battle of Chamdo, in which PRC forces annexed Central Tibet, the Tibetan government, the Ganden Phodrang, invested the Dalai Lama with temporal duties on 17 November 1950 (at 15 years of age), which he held until his exile in 1959.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] During the 1959 Tibetan uprising, the Dalai Lama escaped to India, where he continues to live.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 29 April 1959, the Dalai Lama established the independent Tibetan government in exile in the north Indian hill station of Mussoorie, which then moved in May 1960 to Dharamshala, where he resides.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He retired as political head in 2011 to make way for a democratic government, the Central Tibetan Administration.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama advocates for the welfare of Tibetans and since the early 1970s has called for the Middle Way Approach with China to peacefully resolve the issue of Tibet.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He criticised the CIA Tibetan program, saying that its sudden end in 1972 proved it was primarily aimed at serving American interests.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Up until his mid-80s, the Dalai Lama travelled worldwide to give Tibetan Mahayana and Vajrayana Buddhism teachings, and his Kalachakra teachings and initiations were international events.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He also attended conferences on a wide range of subjects, including the relationship between religion and science, met with other world leaders, religious leaders, philosophers, and scientists, online and in-person.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Since 2018, he has continued to teach on a reduced schedule, limiting his travel to within India only, and occasionally addressing international audiences via live webcasts.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His work includes focus on the environment, economics, women's rights, nonviolence, interfaith dialogue, physics, astronomy, Buddhism and science, cognitive neuroscience, reproductive health and sexuality.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1989.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] *Time* magazine named the Dalai Lama Gandhi's spiritual heir to nonviolence.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In addition, an Indian MP delegation led by Sujeet Kumar, Member of Parliament, Rajya Sabha has advocated for the Dalai Lama to receive the Bharat Ratna, the highest civilian honour in India.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Lhamo Thondup was born on 6 July 1935, to Choekyong Tsering and his wife Dekyi Tsering, a farming and horse trading family in the small hamlet of Taktser under the control of the Ma clique loyal to the Republic of China as part of Qinghai and on the edge of the traditionally Tibetan region of Amdo.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He was one of seven siblings to survive childhood and one of the three supposed reincarnated Rinpoches in the same family.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His eldest sister, Tsering Dolma, was 16 years his senior and was midwife to his mother at his birth.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] She would accompany him into exile and found Tibetan Children's Villages.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His eldest brother, Thupten Jigme Norbu, had been recognised at the age of three by the 13th Dalai Lama as the reincarnation of the high Lama, the 6th Taktser Rinpoche.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His fifth brother, Tendzin Choegyal, had been recognised as the 16th Ngari Rinpoche.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His sister, Jetsun Pema, spent most of her adult life on the Tibetan Children's Villages project.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama has said that his first language was "a broken Xining language which was (a dialect of) the Chinese language, a form of Central Plains Mandarin", and his family speaks neither Amdo Tibetan nor Lhasa Tibetan.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] After the demise of the 13th Dalai Lama, in 1935, the Ordinance of Lama Temple Management was published by the Central Government.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In 1936, the Method of Reincarnation of Lamas was published by the Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission of the Central Government.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 3 states that death of lamas, including the Dalai Lama and Panchen Lama, should be reported to the commission, soul boys should be located and checked by the commission, and a lot-drawing ceremony with the Golden Urn system should be held.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 6 states that local governments should invite officials from the Central Government to take care of the sitting-in-the-bed ceremony.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 7 states that soul boys should not be sought from current lama families.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] This article echoes what the Qianlong Emperor described in The Discourse of Lama to eliminate greedy families with multiple reincarnated rinpoches, lamas.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Based on custom and regulation, the regent was actively involved in the search for the reincarnation of the Dalai Lama.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Following reported signs and visions, three search teams were sent out to the north-east, the east, and the south-east to locate the new incarnation when the boy who was to become the 14th Dalai Lama was about two years old.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Sir Basil Gould, British delegate to Lhasa in 1936, related his account of the north-eastern team to Sir Charles Alfred Bell, former British resident in Lhasa and friend of the 13th Dalai Lama.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Among other omens, the head of the embalmed body of the 13th Dalai Lama, at first facing south-east, had turned to face the north-east, indicating, it was interpreted, the direction in which his successor would be found.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Regent, Reting Rinpoche, shortly afterwards had a vision at the sacred lake of Lhamo La-tso which he interpreted as Amdo being the region to search.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] This vision was also interpreted to refer to a large monastery with a gilded roof and turquoise tiles, and a twisting path from there to a hill to the east, opposite which stood a small house with distinctive eaves.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The team, led by Kewtsang Rinpoche, went first to meet the Panchen Lama, who had been stuck in Jyekundo, in northern Kham.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Panchen Lama had been investigating births of unusual children in the area ever since the death of the 13th Dalai Lama.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He gave Kewtsang the names of three boys whom he had discovered and identified as candidates.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Within a year the Panchen Lama had died.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Two of his three candidates were crossed off the list but the third, a "fearless" child, the most promising, was from Taktser village, which, as in the vision, was on a hill, at the end of a trail leading to Taktser from the great Kumbum Monastery with its gilded, turquoise roof.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] There they found a house, as interpreted from the vision—the house where Lhamo Dhondup lived.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 14th Dalai Lama claims that at the time, the village of Taktser stood right on the "real border" between the region of Amdo and China.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to the search lore, when the team visited, posing as pilgrims, its leader, a Sera Lama, pretended to be the servant and sat separately in the kitchen.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He held an old mala that had belonged to the 13th Dalai Lama, and the boy Lhamo Dhondup, aged two, approached and asked for it.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The monk said, "If you know who I am, you can have it." The child said, "Sera Lama, Sera Lama", and spoke with him in a Lhasa accent, in a dialect the boy's mother could not understand.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The next time the party returned to the house, they revealed their real purpose and asked permission to subject the boy to certain tests.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] One test consisted of showing him various pairs of objects, one of which had belonged to the 13th Dalai Lama and one which had not.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In every case, he chose the Dalai Lama's own objects and rejected the others.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] From 1936 the Hui "Ma clique" Muslim warlord Ma Bufang ruled Qinghai as its governor under the nominal authority of the Republic of China central government.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to an interview with the 14th Dalai Lama, in the 1930s, Ma Bufang had seized this north-east corner of Amdo in the name of Chiang Kai-shek's weak government and incorporated it into the Chinese province of Qinghai.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Before going to Taktser, Kewtsang had gone to Ma Bufang to pay his respects.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] When Ma Bufang heard a candidate had been found in Taktser, he had the family brought to him in Xining.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He first demanded proof that the boy was the Dalai Lama, but the Lhasa government, though informed by Kewtsang that this was the one, told Kewtsang to say he had to go to Lhasa for further tests with other candidates.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] They knew that if he was declared to be the Dalai Lama, the Chinese government would insist on sending a large army escort with him, which would then stay in Lhasa and refuse to budge.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Ma Bufang, together with Kumbum Monastery, then refused to allow him to depart unless he was declared to be the Dalai Lama, but withdrew this demand in return for 100,000 Chinese dollars ransom in silver to be shared among them, to let them go to Lhasa.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Two years of diplomatic wrangling followed before it was accepted by Lhasa that the ransom had to be paid to avoid the Chinese getting involved and escorting him to Lhasa with a large army.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Meanwhile, the boy was kept at Kumbum where two of his brothers were already studying as monks and recognised incarnate lamas.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The payment of 300,000 silver dollars was then advanced by Muslim traders en route to Mecca in a large caravan via Lhasa.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] They paid Ma Bufang on behalf of the Tibetan government against promissory notes to be redeemed, with interest, in Lhasa.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 20,000-dollar fee for an escort was dropped, since the Muslim merchants invited them to join their caravan for protection; Ma Bufang sent 20 of his soldiers with them and was paid from both sides since the Chinese government granted him another 50,000 dollars for the expenses of the journey.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Furthermore, the Indian government helped the Tibetans raise the ransom funds by affording them import concessions.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 22 September 1938, representatives of Tibet Office in Beijing informed Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission that 3 candidates were found and ceremony of Golden Urn would be held in Tibet.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In October 1938, the Method of Using Golden Urn for the 14th Dalai Lama was drafted by Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 12 December 1938, regent Jamphel Yeshe Gyaltsen, the serving Reting Rinpoche, informed the Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission that three candidates were found and ceremony of Golden Urn would be held.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Released from Kumbum, on 21 July 1939 the party travelled across Tibet on a journey to Lhasa in the large Muslim caravan with Lhamo Dhondup, now four years old, riding with his brother Lobsang in a special palanquin carried by two mules, two years after being discovered.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] As soon as they were out of Ma Bufang's area, he was officially declared to be the 14th Dalai Lama by the Kashag, and after ten weeks of travel he arrived in Lhasa on 8 October 1939.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The ordination (pabbajja) and giving of the monastic name of Tenzin Gyatso were arranged by Reting Rinpoche and according to the Dalai Lama "I received my ordination from Kyabjé Ling Rinpoché in the Jokhang in Lhasa." There was very limited Chinese involvement at this time.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The family of the 14th Dalai Lama was elevated to the highest stratum of the Tibetan aristocracy and acquired land and serf holdings, as with the families of previous Dalai Lamas.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In 1959, at the age of 23, he took his final examination at Lhasa's Jokhang Temple during the annual Monlam Prayer Festival.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He passed with honours and was awarded the Lharampa degree, the highest-level *geshe* degree, roughly equivalent to a doctorate in Buddhist philosophy.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to the Dalai Lama, he had a succession of tutors in Tibet including Reting Rinpoche, Tathag Rinpoche, Ling Rinpoche and lastly Trijang Rinpoche, who became junior tutor when he was 19.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] At the age of 11 he met the Austrian mountaineer Heinrich Harrer, who became his videographer and tutor about the world outside Lhasa.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The two remained friends until Harrer's death in 2006.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Historically the Dalai Lamas or their regents held political and religious leadership over Tibet from Lhasa with varying degrees of influence depending on the regions of Tibet and periods of history.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This began with the 5th Dalai Lama's rule in 1642 and lasted until the 1950s (except for 1705–1750), during which period the Dalai Lamas headed the Tibetan government or Ganden Phodrang.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Until 1912 however, when the 13th Dalai Lama declared the complete independence of Tibet, their rule was generally subject to patronage and protection of firstly Mongol kings (1642–1720) and then the Manchu-led Qing dynasty (1720–1912).
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Afterwards in 1939, at the age of four, the Dalai Lama was taken in a procession of lamas to Lhasa.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Former British officials stationed in India and Tibet recalled that envoys from Britain and China were present at the Dalai Lama's enthronement in February 1940.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] According to Basil Gould, the Chinese representative Wu Chunghsin was reportedly unhappy about the position he had during the ceremony.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Afterward an article appeared in the Chinese press falsely claiming that Wu personally announced the installation of the Dalai Lama, who supposedly prostrated himself to Wu in gratitude.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] After his enthronement, the Dalai Lama's childhood was then spent between the Potala Palace and Norbulingka, his summer residence, both of which are now UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chiang Kai Shek ordered Ma Bufang to put his Muslim soldiers on alert for an invasion of Tibet in 1942.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Ma Bufang complied, and moved several thousand troops to the border with Tibet.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chiang also threatened the Tibetans with aerial bombardment if they worked with the Japanese.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Ma Bufang attacked the Tibetan Buddhist Tsang monastery in 1941.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He also constantly attacked the Labrang monastery.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In October 1950 the army of the People's Republic of China marched to the edge of the Dalai Lama's territory and sent a delegation after defeating a legion of the Tibetan army in warlord-controlled Kham.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On 17 November 1950, at the age of 15, the 14th Dalai Lama assumed full temporal (political) power as ruler of Tibet.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's formal rule as head of the government in Tibet was brief although he was enthroned as spiritual leader on 22 February 1940.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] When Chinese cadres entered Tibet in 1950, with a crisis looming, the Dalai Lama was asked to assume the role of head of state at the age of 15, which he did on 17 November 1950.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Customarily the Dalai Lama would typically assume control at about the age of 20.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He sent a delegation to Beijing, which signed the Seventeen Point Agreement.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama believes the draft agreement was written by China.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Tibetan representatives were not allowed to suggest any alterations and China did not allow the Tibetan representatives to communicate with the Tibetan government in Lhasa.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Tibetan delegation was not authorised by Lhasa to sign, but ultimately submitted to pressure from the Chinese to sign anyway, using seals specifically made for the purpose.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Seventeen Point Agreement recognised Chinese sovereignty over Tibet, but China allowed the Dalai Lama to continue to rule Tibet internally, and it allowed the system of feudal peasantry to persist.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In September 1951, following a lengthy discussion with the returning delegates, the National Assembly recommended that the Dalai Lama accept the Seventeen Point Agreement.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He telegraphed his confirmation to Chairman Mao Zedong on 24 October.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Scholar Robert Barnett wrote of the serfdom controversy: "So even if it were agreed that serfdom and feudalism existed in Tibet, this would be little different other than in technicalities from conditions in any other 'premodern' peasant society, including most of China at that time.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The power of the Chinese argument therefore lies in its implication that serfdom, and with it feudalism, is inseparable from extreme abuse.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Evidence to support this linkage has not been found by scholars other than those close to Chinese governmental circles.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The 19-year-old Dalai Lama toured China for almost a year from 1954 to 1955, meeting many of the revolutionary leaders and the top echelon of the Chinese communist leadership who created modern China.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He learned Chinese and socialist ideals, as explained by his Chinese hosts, on a tour of China showcasing the benefits of socialism and the effective governance provided to turn the large, impoverished nation into a modern and egalitarian society, which impressed him.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In September 1954, he went to the Chinese capital to meet Chairman Mao Zedong with the 10th Panchen Lama and attend the 1st National People's Congress as a delegate, primarily discussing China's constitution.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On 27 September 1954, the Dalai Lama was selected as a Vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, a post he officially held until 1964.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1956, on a trip to India to celebrate the Buddha's Birthday, the Dalai Lama asked the Prime Minister of India, Jawaharlal Nehru, if he would allow him political asylum should he choose to stay.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Nehru discouraged this as a provocation against peace, and reminded him of the Indian Government's non-interventionist stance agreed upon with its 1954 treaty with China.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Long called a "splittist" and "traitor" by China, the Dalai Lama has attempted formal talks over Tibet's status in China.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Chinese Foreign Ministry has warned the US and other countries to "shun" the Dalai Lama during visits and often uses trade negotiations and human rights talks as an incentive to do so.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] China sporadically bans images of the Dalai Lama and arrests citizens for owning photos of him in Tibet.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In April 2018, the Dalai Lama confirmed Chinese government claims about Gedhun Choekyi Nyima by saying that he knew from "reliable sources" that the Panchen Lama he had recognised was alive and receiving normal education.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He said he hoped that the Chinese-recognised Panchen Lama (Gyaincain Norbu) studied well under the guidance of a good teacher, adding that there were instances in Tibetan Buddhist tradition, of a reincarnated lama taking more than one manifestation.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is a target of Chinese state sponsored hacking.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Security experts claim "targeting Tibetan activists is a strong indicator of official Chinese government involvement" since economic information is the primary goal of private Chinese hackers.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2009 the personal office of the Dalai Lama asked researchers at the Munk Center for International Studies at the University of Toronto to check its computers for malicious software.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] A second cyberspy network, Shadow Network, was discovered by the same researchers in 2010.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Stolen documents included a year's worth of the Dalai Lama's personal email, and classified government material relating to India, West Africa, the Russian Federation, the Middle East, and NATO.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] "Sophisticated" hackers were linked to universities in China, Beijing again denied involvement.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chinese hackers posing as The New York Times, Amnesty International and other organisation's reporters targeted the private office of the Dalai Lama, Tibetan Parliament members, and Tibetan nongovernmental organisations, among others, in 2019.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] At the outset of the 1959 Tibetan uprising, fearing for his life, the Dalai Lama and his retinue fled Tibet with the help of the CIA's Special Activities Division, crossing into India on 30 March 1959, reaching Tezpur in Assam on 18 April.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Some time later he set up the Government of Tibet in Exile in Dharamshala, India, which is often referred to as "*Little Lhasa*".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] After the founding of the government in exile he re-established the approximately 80,000 Tibetan refugees who followed him into exile in agricultural settlements.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He created a Tibetan educational system in order to teach the Tibetan children the language, history, religion, and culture.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Tibetan Institute of Performing Arts was established in 1959 and the Central Institute of Higher Tibetan Studies became the primary university for Tibetans in India in 1967.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He supported the refounding of 200 monasteries and nunneries in an attempt to preserve Tibetan Buddhist teachings and the Tibetan way of life.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama appealed to the United Nations on the rights of Tibetans.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This appeal resulted in three resolutions adopted by the General Assembly in 1959, 1961, and 1965, all before the People's Republic was allowed representation at the United Nations.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The resolutions called on China to respect the human rights of Tibetans.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1963, he promulgated a democratic constitution which is based upon the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, creating an elected parliament and an administration to champion his cause.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1970, he opened the Library of Tibetan Works and Archives in Dharamshala which houses over 80,000 manuscripts and important knowledge resources related to Tibetan history, politics and culture.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] It is considered one of the most important institutions for Tibetology in the world.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2016, there were demands from Indian citizens and politicians of different political parties to confer the Dalai Lama the prestigious Bharat Ratna, the highest civilian honour of India, which has only been awarded to a non-Indian citizen twice in its history.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2021, it was revealed that the Dalai Lama's inner circle were listed in the Pegasus project data as having been targeted with spyware on their phones.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Analysis strongly indicates potential targets were selected by the Indian government.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2025, Indian Members of Parliament (MPs), led by Sujeet Kumar, BJP Rajya Sabha MP, called for His Holiness to be awarded the Bharat Ratna.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] At the Congressional Human Rights Caucus in 1987 in Washington, D.C., the Dalai Lama gave a speech outlining his ideas for the future status of Tibet.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The plan called for Tibet to become a democratic "zone of peace" without nuclear weapons, and with support for human rights.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The plan would come to be known as the "Strasbourg proposal", because the Dalai Lama expanded on the plan at Strasbourg on 15 June 1988.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] There, he proposed the creation of a self-governing Tibet "in association with the People's Republic of China." This would have been pursued by negotiations with the PRC government, but the plan was rejected by the Tibetan Government-in-Exile in 1991.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama has indicated that he wishes to return to Tibet only if the People's Republic of China agrees not to make any precondition for his return.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In the 1970s, the Paramount leader Deng Xiaoping set China's sole return requirement to the Dalai Lama as that he "must [come back] as a Chinese citizen ... that is, patriotism".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama celebrated his 70th birthday on 6 July 2005.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] About 10,000 Tibetan refugees, monks and foreign tourists gathered outside his home.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Patriarch Alexius II of the Russian Orthodox Church alleged positive relations with Buddhists.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] However, later that year, the Russian state prevented the Dalai Lama from fulfilling an invitation to the traditionally Buddhist republic of Kalmykia.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The President of the Republic of China (Taiwan), Chen Shui-bian, attended an evening celebrating the Dalai Lama's birthday at the Chiang Kai-shek Memorial Hall in Taipei.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In October 2008 in Japan, the Dalai Lama addressed the 2008 Tibetan violence that had erupted and that the Chinese government accused him of fomenting.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He responded that he had "lost faith" in efforts to negotiate with the Chinese government, and that it was "up to the Tibetan people" to decide what to do.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] During his visit to Taiwan after Typhoon Morakot 30 Taiwanese indigenous peoples protested against the Dalai Lama and denounced it as politically motivated.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is an advocate for a world free of nuclear weapons, and serves on the Advisory Council of the Nuclear Age Peace Foundation.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama has voiced his support for the Campaign for the Establishment of a United Nations Parliamentary Assembly, an organisation which campaigns for democratic reformation of the United Nations, and the creation of a more accountable international political system.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Until reaching his mid-80s, the Dalai Lama maintained a busy international lecture and teaching schedule.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Since 2018, he has continued to teach, but has limited his travel to within India only.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] His public talks and teachings are usually webcast live in multiple languages, via an inviting organisation's website, or on the Dalai Lama's own website.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Scores of his past teaching videos can be viewed there, as well as public talks, conferences, interviews, dialogues and panel discussions.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's best known teaching subject is the Kalachakra tantra which, as of 2014, he had conferred a total of 33 times, most often in India's upper Himalayan regions but also in the Western world.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Kalachakra (Wheel of Time) is one of the most complex teachings of Buddhism, sometimes taking two weeks to confer, and he often confers it on very large audiences, up to 200,000 students and disciples at a time.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is the author of numerous books on Buddhism, many of them on general Buddhist subjects but also including books on particular topics like Dzogchen, a Nyingma practice.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Since 2018, his schedule has contained fewer engagements, with most occurring in India along with a handful webcasts to international audiences.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Again in London in 1996 he taught the Four Noble Truths, the basis and foundation of Buddhism accepted by all Buddhists, at the combined invitation of 27 different Buddhist organisations of all schools and traditions belonging to the Network of Buddhist Organisations UK.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In India, no fees are charged to attend these teachings since costs are covered by requesting sponsors.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] When he travels abroad to give teachings there is usually a ticket fee calculated by the inviting organisation to cover the costs involved and any surplus is normally to be donated to recognised charities.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has frequently visited and lectured at colleges and universities, some of which have conferred honorary degrees upon him.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Dozens of videos of recorded webcasts of the Dalai Lama's public talks on general subjects for non-Buddhists like peace, happiness and compassion, modern ethics, the environment, economic and social issues, gender, the empowerment of women and so forth can be viewed in his office's archive.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama met Pope Paul VI at the Vatican in 1973.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1990, he met a delegation of Jewish teachers in Dharamshala for an extensive interfaith dialogue.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has since visited Israel three times, and in 2006 met the Chief Rabbi of Israel.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2006, he met Pope Benedict XVI privately.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has met the Archbishop of Canterbury, Dr.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Robert Runcie, and other leaders of the Anglican Church in London, Gordon B.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Hinckley, who at the time was the president of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, as well as senior Eastern Orthodox Church, Muslim, Hindu, Jewish, and Sikh officials.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1996 and 2002, he participated in the first two Gethsemani Encounters hosted by the Monastic Interreligious Dialogue at the Abbey of Our Lady of Gethsemani, where Thomas Merton, whom the Dalai Lama had met in the late 1960s, had lived.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He is also a member of the Board of World Religious Leaders as part of The Elijah Interfaith Institute and participated in the Third Meeting of the Board of World Religious Leaders in Amritsar, India, on 26 November 2007 to discuss the topic of Love and Forgiveness.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2009, the Dalai Lama inaugurated an interfaith "World Religions-Dialogue and Symphony" conference at Gujarat's Mahuva religions, according to Morari Bapu.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2010, the Dalai Lama, joined by a panel of scholars, launched the Common Ground Project, in Bloomington, Indiana (USA), which was planned by himself and Prince Ghazi bin Muhammad of Jordan during several years of personal conversations.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The project is based on the book *Common Ground between Islam and Buddhism*.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2019, the Dalai Lama fully sponsored the first-ever 'Celebrating Diversity in the Muslim World' conference in New Delhi on behalf of the Muslims of Ladakh.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's lifelong interest in science and technology dates from his childhood in Lhasa, Tibet, when he was fascinated by mechanical objects like clocks, watches, telescopes, film projectors, clockwork soldiers and motor cars, and loved to repair, disassemble and reassemble them.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Once, observing the Moon through a telescope as a child, he realised it was a crater-pocked lump of rock and not a heavenly body emitting its own light as Tibetan cosmologists had taught him.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has also said that had he not been brought up as a monk he would probably have been an engineer.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On his first trip to the west in 1973 he asked to visit Cambridge University's astrophysics department in the UK and he sought out renowned scientists such as Sir Karl Popper, David Bohm and Carl Friedrich von Weizsäcker, who taught him the basics of science.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama sees important common ground between science and Buddhism in having the same approach to challenge dogma on the basis of empirical evidence that comes from observation and analysis of phenomena.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Also in 1983, the American social entrepreneur and innovator R.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Adam Engle, who had become aware of the Dalai Lama's deep interest in science, was already considering the idea of facilitating for him a serious dialogue with a selection of appropriate scientists.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1984 Engle formally offered to the Dalai Lama's office to organise a week-long, formal dialogue for him with a suitable team of scientists, provided that the Dalai Lama would wish to fully participate in such a dialogue.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Within 48 hours the Dalai Lama confirmed to Engle that he was "truly interested in participating in something substantial about science" so Engle proceeded with launching the project.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Francisco Varela, having heard about Engle's proposal, then called him to tell him of his earlier discussions with the Dalai Lama and to offer his scientific collaboration to the project.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Engle accepted, and Varela assisted him to assemble his team of six specialist scientists for the first 'Mind and Life' dialogue on the cognitive sciences, which was eventually held with the Dalai Lama at his residence in Dharamsala in 1987.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This five-day event was so successful that at the end the Dalai Lama told Engle he would very much like to repeat it again in the future.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] As Mind and Life Institute's remit expanded, Engle formalised the organisation as a non-profit foundation after the third dialogue, held in 1990, which initiated the undertaking of neurobiological research programmes in the United States under scientific conditions.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Sponsors and partners in these dialogues have included the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Johns Hopkins University, the Mayo Clinic, and Zurich University.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Apart from time spent teaching Buddhism and fulfilling responsibilities to his Tibetan followers, the Dalai Lama spends time and resources investigating the interface between Buddhism and science through the ongoing series of Mind and Life dialogues and its spin-offs.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] As the institute's Cofounder and the Honorary chairman he has personally presided over and participated in all its dialogues, which continue to expand worldwide.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] These activities have given rise to dozens of DVD sets of the dialogues and books he has authored on them such as *Ethics for the New Millennium* and *The Universe in a Single Atom*, as well as scientific papers and university research programmes.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On the Tibetan and Buddhist side, science subjects have been added to the curriculum for Tibetan monastic educational institutions and scholarship.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] SEE learning focuses on developing critical thinking, ethical reasoning and compassion and stresses on commonalities rather than on the differences.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In particular, the Mind and Life Education Humanities & Social Sciences initiatives have been instrumental in developing the emerging field of Contemplative Science, by researching, for example, the effects of contemplative practice on the human brain, behaviour and biology.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] These activities have even had an impact in the Chinese capital.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2013 an 'academic dialogue' with a Chinese scientist, a Tibetan 'living Buddha' and a professor of Religion took place in Beijing.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Entitled "High-end dialogue: ancient Buddhism and modern science" it addressed the same considerations that interest the Dalai Lama, described as 'discussing about the similarities between Buddhism and modern science'.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama uses various meditation techniques, including analytic meditation and emptiness meditation.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2007, the 14th Dalai Lama said his reincarnation could be a woman.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This was mentioned again in 2015 and 2019.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In May 2011, the Dalai Lama retired from the Central Tibetan Administration.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2011, the Dalai Lama repeated his statement in an interview with Canadian CTV News.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He added that Chinese laws banning the selection of successors based on reincarnation will not impact his decisions.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] "Naturally my next life is entirely up to me.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] And also this is not a political matter", he said in the interview.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama also added that he has not decided on whether he would reincarnate or be the last Dalai Lama.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In an interview with the German newspaper *Welt am Sonntag* published on 7 September 2014 the Dalai Lama stated "the institution of the Dalai Lama has served its purpose", and that "We had a Dalai Lama for almost five centuries.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The 14th Dalai Lama now is very popular.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Let us then finish with a popular Dalai Lama." In response, the Chinese government said the title of Dalai Lama has been conferred by the central government for hundreds of years and the 14th Dalai Lama has ulterior motives.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This was taken by Tibetan activists and *The Wire* to mean that China will make the Dalai Lama reincarnate no matter what.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Gyatso has also expressed fear that the Chinese government would manipulate any reincarnation selection in order to choose a successor that would go along with their political goals.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2015, the 14th Dalai Lama has claimed he may be reincarnated as a mischievous blonde woman.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2019, the 14th Dalai Lama said that if a female Dalai Lama comes, she should be more attractive.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Chinese politician Padma Choling accused the 14th Dalai Lama of flip-flopping with his various statements on the issue, and of hypocrisy as he himself was reincarnated.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He also accused the 14th Dalai Lama of profaning Tibetan Buddhism "by doubting his reincarnation".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2019, the 14th Dalai Lama stated that because of the feudal origin of the Dalai Lama reincarnation system, the reincarnation system should end.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, in July 2025, as the 14th Dalai Lama reached the age of 90, he addressed growing discussions about his succession by reaffirming that he will be reincarnated and that the process of identifying his successor should follow traditional Tibetan Buddhist practices.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a message shared during a prayer ceremony and posted on social media, the Dalai Lama stated that only his non-profit institution, Gaden Phodrang Foundation of the Dalai Lama, has the legitimate authority to oversee the selection of his reincarnation.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He emphasised that the identification of the 15th Dalai Lama should involve consultation with senior leaders of Tibetan Buddhist schools and with spiritual entities known as oath-bound Dharma Protectors, following established historical customs.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama reaffirmed that his reincarnation will occur outside China.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a direct challenge to China, he asserted that the centuries-old spiritual institution bearing his name will endure beyond his death, emphasising that only his inner circle—not Beijing—will have the authority to identify his successor.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has stated that his successor will be born in a free country, suggesting that the next reincarnation could come from the Tibetan diaspora—around 140,000 people worldwide, with about half residing in India.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In response, the Chinese government rejected the Dalai Lama's position.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Officials in Beijing stated that the reincarnation of the Dalai Lama, as well as other high-ranking Tibetan Buddhist figures such as the Panchen Lama, must be approved by the central government.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to the Chinese Foreign Ministry, the government holds ultimate authority in confirming the identity of reincarnated Tibetan spiritual leaders.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Samdhong Rinpoche Lobsang Tenzin, a senior leader of the Dalai Lama's trust, affirmed the continuation of the Dalai Lama institution, stating that both a 15th and 16th Dalai Lama would follow.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said the current Dalai Lama would issue guidelines for identifying his successor.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Deputy speaker of the parliament of the Central Tibetan Administration Dolma Tsering Teykhang accused China of trying to control the reincarnation process and emphasised the need for the Dalai Lama to address the world directly.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his book, *Voice for the Voiceless*, published in 2025, the 14th Dalai Lama said Tibetans worldwide want the institution of the Dalai Lama to continue after his death and specified that his successor would be born in the "free world".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Despite initially advocating for Tibetan independence from 1961 to 1974, the Dalai Lama no longer supports it.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Instead he advocates for more meaningful autonomy for Tibetans within the People's Republic of China.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This approach is known as the "Middle Way".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2005, the 14th Dalai Lama emphasised that Tibet is a part of China, and Tibetan culture and Buddhism are part of Chinese culture.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a speech at Kolkata in 2017, the Dalai Lama stated that Tibetans wanted to stay with China and they did not desire independence.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said that he believed that China after opening up, had changed 40 to 50 per cent of what it was earlier, and that Tibetans wanted to get more development from China.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2020, the Dalai Lama stated that he did not support Tibetan independence and hoped to visit China as a Nobel Prize winner.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said "I prefer the concept of a 'republic' in the People's Republic of China.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama maintains close ties with India.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2008, the Dalai Lama said that Arunachal Pradesh, partially claimed by China, is part of India, citing the disputed 1914 Simla Accord.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Dhundup Gyalpo, the Dalai Lama's eventual secretary in New Delhi, argued that Tibetan and Chinese peoples have no connections apart from a few culinary dishes and that Chinese Buddhists could also be deemed "Indian in spirituality", because both Tibetan and Chinese Buddhism originated from India.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has said that, from the perspective of the Buddhist precepts, abortion is an act of killing.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1993, he clarified a more nuanced position, stating, "... it depends on the circumstances.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] If the unborn child will be retarded or if the birth will create serious problems for the parent, these are cases where there can be an exception.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has repeatedly expressed his opposition to the death penalty, saying that it contradicts the Buddhist philosophy of non-violence and that it expresses anger, not compassion.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] During a 2005 visit to Japan, a country which has the death penalty, the Dalai Lama called for the abolition of the death penalty and said in his address, "Criminals, people who commit crimes, usually society rejects these people.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Give them some form of punishment to say they were wrong, but show them they are part of society and can change.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Show them compassion." The Dalai Lama has also praised US states that have abolished the death penalty.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama says that he is active in spreading India's message of nonviolence and religious harmony throughout the world.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] "I am the messenger of India's ancient thoughts the world over." He has said that democracy has deep roots in India.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He says he considers India the master and Tibet its disciple, as great scholars went from India to Tibet to teach Buddhism.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has noted that millions of people lost their lives in violence and the economies of many countries were ruined due to conflicts in the 20th century.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has also critiqued proselytisation and certain types of conversion, believing the practices to be contrary to the fundamental ideas of religious harmony and spiritual practice.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has stated that "It's very important that our religious traditions live in harmony with one another and I don't think proselytizing contributes to this.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1993, the Dalai Lama attended the World Conference on Human Rights and made a speech titled "Human Rights and Universal Responsibility".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2001, in response to a question from a Seattle schoolgirl, the Dalai Lama said that it is permissible to shoot someone in self-defence (if the person was "trying to kill you") and he emphasised that the shot should not be fatal.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2013, the Dalai Lama criticised Buddhist monks' attacks on Muslims in Myanmar and rejected violence by Buddhists, saying: "Buddha always teaches us about forgiveness, tolerance, compassion.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] If from one corner of your mind, some emotion makes you want to hit, or want to kill, then please remember Buddha's faith. ...
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] All problems must be solved through dialogue, through talk.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has consistently praised India.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In December 2018, he said Muslim countries like Bangladesh, Pakistan and Syria should learn about religion from India for peace in the world.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] When asked in 2019 about attacks on the minority community in India including a recent one against a Muslim family in Gurgaon, he said: "There are always a few mischievous people, but that does not mean it a symbol of that nation".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He reiterated in December 2021 that he thought India was a role model for religious harmony in the world.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama advocates compassion for animals and frequently urges people to try vegetarianism or at least reduce their consumption of meat.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In Tibet, where historically meat was the most common food, most monks historically have been omnivores, including the Dalai Lamas.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Fourteenth Dalai Lama was raised in a meat-eating family but converted to vegetarianism after arriving in India, where vegetables are much more easily available and vegetarianism is widespread.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He spent many years as a vegetarian, but after contracting hepatitis in India and suffering from weakness, his doctors told him to return to eating meat which he now does twice a week.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This attracted public attention when, during a visit to the White House, he was offered a vegetarian menu but declined by replying, as he is known to do on occasion when dining in the company of non-vegetarians, "I'm a Tibetan monk, not a vegetarian".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His own home kitchen, however, is completely vegetarian.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2009, the English singer Paul McCartney wrote a letter to the Dalai Lama inquiring why he was not a vegetarian.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] As McCartney later told *The Guardian*, "He wrote back very kindly, saying, 'my doctors tell me that I must eat meat'.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] And I wrote back again, saying, you know, I don't think that's right. [...] I think now he's vegetarian most of the time.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] I think he's now being told, the more he meets doctors from the west, that he can get his protein somewhere else. [...] It just doesn't seem right – the Dalai Lama, on the one hand, saying, 'Hey guys, don't harm sentient beings...
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has referred to himself as a Marxist and has articulated criticisms of capitalism.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He reports hearing of communism when he was very young, but only in the context of the destruction of the Mongolian People's Republic.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] It was only when he went on his trip to Beijing that he learned about Marxist theory from his interpreter Baba Phuntsog Wangyal of the Tibetan Communist Party.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] At that time, he reports, "I was so attracted to Marxism, I even expressed my wish to become a Communist Party member", citing his favourite concepts of self-sufficiency and equal distribution of wealth.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He does not believe that China implemented "true Marxist policy", and thinks the historical communist states such as the Soviet Union "were far more concerned with their narrow national interests than with the Workers' International".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Moreover, he believes one flaw of historically "Marxist regimes" is that they place too much emphasis on destroying the ruling class, and not enough on compassion.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He finds Marxism superior to capitalism, believing the latter is only concerned with "how to make profits", whereas the former has "moral ethics".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] On India–Pakistan relations, the Dalai Lama in October 2019 said: "There is a difference between Indian and Pakistani Prime Minister's speech at the UN.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Indian Prime Minister talks about peace, and you know what his Pakistan counterpart said, getting China's political support is Pakistan's compulsion.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Pakistani leaders should calm down and think beyond emotions and should follow a realistic approach".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama is outspoken in his concerns about environmental problems, frequently giving public talks on themes related to the environment.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has pointed out that many rivers in Asia originate in Tibet, and that the melting of Himalayan glaciers could affect the countries in which the rivers flow.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He acknowledged official Chinese laws against deforestation in Tibet, but lamented they can be ignored due to possible corruption.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He was quoted as saying "ecology should be part of our daily life"; personally, he takes showers instead of baths, and turns lights off when he leaves a room.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Around 2005, he started campaigning for wildlife conservation, including by issuing a religious ruling against wearing tiger and leopard skins as garments.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama supports the anti-whaling position in the whaling controversy, but has criticised the activities of groups such as the Sea Shepherd Conservation Society (which carries out acts of what it calls aggressive nonviolence against property).
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Before the 2009 United Nations Climate Change Conference, he urged national leaders to put aside domestic concerns and take collective action against climate change.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's stances on topics of sexuality have changed over time.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] A monk since childhood, the Dalai Lama has said that sex offers fleeting satisfaction and leads to trouble later, while chastity offers a better life and "more independence, more freedom".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has said that problems arising from conjugal life sometimes even lead to suicide or murder.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has asserted that all religions have the same view about adultery.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, he also says that in modern times all common, consensual sexual practices that do not cause harm to others are ethically acceptable and that society should accept and respect people who are gay or transgender from a secular point of view.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his 1996 book *Beyond Dogma*, he described a traditional Buddhist definition of an appropriate sexual act as follows: "A sexual act is deemed proper when the couples use the organs intended for sexual intercourse and nothing else ...
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Homosexuality, whether it is between men or between women, is not improper in itself.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] What is improper is the use of organs already defined as inappropriate for sexual contact." He elaborated in 1997, conceding that the basis of that teaching was unknown to him.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He also conveyed his own "willingness to consider the possibility that some of the teachings may be specific to a particular cultural and historic context".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2006, the Dalai Lama has expressed concern at "reports of violence and discrimination against" LGBT people and urged "respect, tolerance and the full recognition of human rights for all".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a 2014 interview with Larry King, the Dalai Lama expressed that same-sex marriage is a personal issue, can be ethically socially accepted, and that he personally accepts it.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, he also stated that if same-sex marriage is in contradiction with one's chosen traditions, then they should not follow it.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2009, on gender equality and sexism, the Dalai Lama proclaimed at the National Civil Rights Museum in Memphis, Tennessee: "I call myself a feminist.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Isn't that what you call someone who fights for women's rights?" He also said that by nature, women are more compassionate based on their biology and capacity for reproduction and maternal care.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He called on women to "lead and create a more compassionate world", citing the good works of nurses and mothers.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2015 the Dalai Lama said in a BBC interview that if a female were to succeed him, "that female must be attractive, otherwise it is not much use." When asked if he was joking, he replied, "No.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] True!" The Dalai Lama followed with a joke about his success being due to his own appearance.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His office later released a statement of apology citing the interaction as a translation error.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a 2020 statement in *Time* magazine on the COVID-19 pandemic, the Dalai Lama said that the pandemic must be combated with compassion, empirical science, prayer, and the courage of healthcare workers.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He emphasised "emotional disarmament" (seeing things with a clear and realistic perspective, without fear or rage) and wrote: "The outbreak of this terrible coronavirus has shown that what happens to one person can soon affect every other being.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In September 2018, speaking at a conference in Malmö, Sweden, the Dalai Lama said "I think Europe belongs to the Europeans", but also that Europe was "morally responsible" for helping "a refugee really facing danger against their life".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He stated that Europe has a responsibility to refugees to "receive them, help them, educate them", but that they should aim to return to their places of origin and that "they ultimately should rebuild their own country".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Speaking to German reporters in 2016, the Dalai Lama said there are "too many" refugees in Europe, adding that "Europe, for example Germany, cannot become an Arab country." He also said that "Germany is Germany".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Dorje Shugden is an entity in Tibetan Buddhism that, since the 1930s, has become a point of contention over whether to include or exclude certain non-Gelug teachings.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After the 1975 publication of the *Yellow Book* containing stories about Dorje Shugden acting wrathfully against Gelugpas who also practised Nyingma, the 14th Dalai Lama, himself a Gelugpa and advocate of an inclusive approach, publicly renounced the practice of Dorje Shugden.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Several groups broke away as a result, notably the New Kadampa Tradition (NKT).
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to Tibetologists, the Dalai Lama's disapproval has reduced the prevalence of Shugden sects among Tibetans in China and India.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Shugden devotees have since complained about being ostracised when trying to get jobs or receive services.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's supporters expressed that any discrimination is neither systematic nor encouraged by him.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some Shugden movements such as the NKT have organised demonstrations as a form of protest.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some journalists have suggested that the Chinese government has taken advantage of the controversy.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His office said that there was no ban or discrimination against Shugden worshippers.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 1998, the Dalai Lama's administration acknowledged that it received $1.7 million a year in the 1960s from the US government through a Central Intelligence Agency program.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] When asked by CIA officer John Kenneth Knaus in 1995 to comment on the CIA Tibetan program, the Dalai Lama replied that though it helped the morale of those resisting the Chinese, "thousands of lives were lost in the resistance" and further, that "the U.S.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Government had involved itself in his country's affairs not to help Tibet but only as a Cold War tactic to challenge the Chinese." As part of the program the Dalai Lama received 180,000 dollars a year from 1959 till 1974 for his own personal use.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His administration's reception of CIA funding has become one of the grounds for some state-run Chinese newspapers to discredit him along with the Tibetan independence movement.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his autobiography *Freedom in Exile*, the Dalai Lama criticised the CIA again for supporting the Tibetan independence movement "not because they (the CIA) cared about Tibetan independence, but as part of their worldwide efforts to destabilize all communist governments".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama places highly in global surveys of the world's most admired men, ranking with Pope Francis as among the world's religious leaders cited as the most admired.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's appeal is variously ascribed to his charismatic personality, international fascination with Buddhism, his universalist values, and international sympathy for the Tibetans.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In the 1990s, many films were released by the American film industry about Tibet, including biopics of the Dalai Lama.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This is attributed to both the Dalai Lama's 1989 Nobel Peace Prize as well as to the euphoria following the Fall of Communism.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The most notable films, *Kundun* and *Seven Years in Tibet* (both released in 1997), portrayed "an idyllic pre-1950 Tibet, with a smiling, soft-spoken Dalai Lama at the helm—a Dalai Lama sworn to non-violence": portrayals the Chinese government decried as ahistorical.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has his own pages on Twitter, Facebook and Instagram.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has tried to mobilise international support for Tibetan activities.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has been successful in gaining Western support for himself and the cause of greater Tibetan autonomy, including vocal support from numerous Hollywood celebrities, most notably the actors Richard Gere and Steven Seagal, as well as lawmakers from several major countries.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Photos of the Dalai Lama were banned after March 1959 Lhasa protests until after the end of the Cultural Revolution in 1976.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1996 the Chinese Communist Party once again reinstated the total prohibition of any photo of the 14th Dalai Lama.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to the Tibet Information Network, "authorities in Tibet have begun banning photographs of the exiled Dalai Lama in monasteries and public places, according to reports from a monitoring group and a Tibetan newspaper.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Plainclothes police went to hotels and restaurants in Lhasa, the Tibetan capital, on 22 and 23 April and ordered Tibetans to remove pictures of the Dalai Lama ..." The ban continues in many locations throughout Tibet today.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In popular media, the Dalai Lama appeared on the HBO late-night talk show *Last Week Tonight with John Oliver* on 5 March 2017, where he discussed issues including Tibetan sovereignty, Tibetan self-immolations, and his succession plans.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] A biographical graphic novel, *Man of Peace*, also envisaging the Dalai Lama's return to Tibet, was published by Tibet House US.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] *The Extraordinary Life of His Holiness the Fourteenth Dalai Lama: An Illuminated Journey,* illustrations and text by artist Rima Fujita, narrated by the Dalai Lama, was published by Simon and Schuster in 2021.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has received numerous awards and honours worldwide over his spiritual and political career.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] For a more complete list see Awards and honours presented to the 14th Dalai Lama.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests and massacre, the Norwegian Nobel Committee awarded him the 1989 Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Committee officially gave the prize to the Dalai Lama for "the struggle of the liberation of Tibet and the efforts for a peaceful resolution" and "in part a tribute to the memory of Mahatma Gandhi".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2006, he became one of only six people ever to be granted Honorary Citizenship of Canada.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2007 he was named Presidential Distinguished Professor at Emory University in Atlanta, Georgia, the first time he accepted a university appointment.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He is the chief Patron of the Maha Bodhi Society of India, conferred upon him at the 2008 Annual General Meeting of the Maha Bodhi Society of India.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] At the 68th Annual Grammy Awards, he won the Grammy Award for Best Audio Book, Narration & Storytelling Recording.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a February 2023 video, the Dalai Lama was seen kissing a boy on the lips and asking the child to suck his tongue.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The incident took place at his temple in Dharamshala, Himachal Pradesh, India.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Nearly 100 students were in attendance, as well as the boy's mother, a trustee of the event's organiser.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Her son had requested a hug from the Dalai Lama, who then asked for and received a kiss from the child, pulling him closer to touch lips.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After a pause, the Dalai Lama said "suck my tongue" and, with his tongue out, leaned toward the boy, who appeared nervous and withdrew after sticking out his own tongue.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In an interview clip released by Voice of Tibet, the boy later said it had been a "good experience" meeting the Dalai Lama, from whom he received a lot of "positive energy".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The interaction was originally recorded by Voice of America, which posted the footage after editing out the "suck my tongue" part.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The removed portion of the clip resurfaced in April 2023, and the Dalai Lama's conduct received negative media coverage.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some victim groups and media commentators raised concerns of "child abuse", while the Tibetan Legal Association warned four Indian news outlets to retract parts of their reporting.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The office of His Holiness issued a statement saying that the Dalai Lama often teases "in an innocent and playful way", adding that he "wishes to apologize to the boy and his family ... for the hurt his words may have caused" and "regrets the incident".
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Penpa Tsering, the political leader of the Central Tibetan Administration, called the gesture an "innocent grandfatherly affectionate demeanour" followed by a "jovial prank" with a tongue.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He and other Tibetans accused "pro-Chinese sources" of being behind the video but have not provided any evidence.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some academics, Tibetan leaders and cultural groups described the situation as a cultural misunderstanding.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] They mentioned that sticking out one's tongue is a form of traditional Tibetan greeting to show respect or agreement, stemming from a tradition of performing the gesture to demonstrate that one is not reincarnated from the malevolent king Langdarma, who was said to have a black tongue.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The practice is not known to involve "sucking", however.
[src:ken-burns/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The controversy also drew attention to past incidents where the Dalai Lama caressed the arm of a disabled girl sitting next to him and touched Lady Gaga's knee through her torn trousers before the star laughed.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] There are also two other varieties of Super 8 – Single 8 mm and Straight-8 – that require different cameras but produce a final film with the same dimensions.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] The standard 8 mm (also known as regular 8 or double 8) film format was developed by the Eastman Kodak company during the Great Depression and released to the market in 1932 to create a home movie format that was less expensive than 16 mm.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Double 8 spools actually contain a 16 mm film with twice as many perforations along each edge as normal 16 mm film; on its first pass through the camera, the film is exposed only along half of its width.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] When the first pass is complete, the operator opens the camera and flips and swaps the spools (the design of the spool hole ensures that the operator does this properly) and the same film is subsequently exposed along its other edge, the edge left unexposed on the first pass.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] After the film is developed, the processor splits it down the middle, resulting in two lengths of 8 mm film, each with a single row of perforations along one edge.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Each frame is half the width and half the height of a 16 mm frame, so there are four times the number of frames in a given film area, which is what makes it cost less.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Because of the two passes of the film, the format was sometimes called *Double 8*.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] The frame size of regular 8 mm is 4.8 mm × 3.5 mm, and 1 meter of film contains 264 pictures.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Normally, Double 8 is filmed at 16 or 18 frames per second.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Common length film spools allowed filming of about 3 to 4+1⁄2 minutes at 12, 15, 16, and 18 frames per second.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Kodak ceased sales of standard 8 mm film under its own brand in the early 1990s but continued to manufacture the film, which was sold via independent film stores.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Black-and-white 8 mm film is still manufactured in the Czech Republic, and several companies buy bulk quantities of 16 mm film to make regular 8 mm by re-perforating the stock, cutting it into 25 foot (7.6 m) lengths, and collecting it into special standard 8 mm spools, which they then sell.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Re-perforation requires special equipment.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Some specialists also produce Super 8 mm film from existing 16 mm or even 35 mm film stock.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] When Eastman Kodak first conceived the 8 mm format, no provision was made for the addition of a sound track.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Nevertheless, in the 1960s, projectors appeared on the market that were capable of recording and replaying sound from a magnetic stripe applied to the film after it had been processed.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] The only part of the film wide enough to accept such a magnetic stripe was the area between the edge and the perforations.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] A much narrower stripe was sometimes added to the opposite edge so that the film piled up evenly on the spool, but was never used for sound.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] The sound to picture separation was the same dimensionally as 16 mm film, and as that format is 28 frames, that meant that the Double-8 system was 56 frames.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] The proximity of the sound stripe to the perforations caused some problems in keeping the film in close contact with the sound head.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] A few sound prints appeared for use in Double 8 projectors.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] In 1965, Super-8 film was released and was quickly adopted by many amateur film-makers.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] It featured a better quality image and was easier to use mainly due to a cartridge-loading system that did not require reloading and rethreading halfway through.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] To easily differentiate Super 8 film from Standard 8, projector spools for the former had larger spindle holes.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Therefore, it was not possible to mount a Super 8 spool on a Standard 8 projector, and vice versa.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] The Super 8 format was designed from the start to accommodate a sound track (one of the few film formats to do so).
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] This track would occupy the area between the edge of the film and the image area.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] As in the double 8 system, a second stripe was sometimes added between the edge and the perforations.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] The image to sound distance was much shorter for the Super 8 system at just 18 frames.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] At first, the magnetic stripe had to be applied after the film was processed and recorded on a suitable projector.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] In the 1970s, cameras appeared which were able to record live sound directly onto pre-striped film.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] This film was loaded into oversize cartridges that provided access for the camera's sound recording head.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] The camera would also accept non sound cartridges, but silent cameras could not accept sound cartridges.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] One major advantage of the Super 8 system was that as the camera pressure plate was a part of the cartridge, it could be moulded to the profile of the stripe(s) on the film.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Projectors also appeared on the market which took advantage of the balance stripe next to the perforations by recording and replaying stereo sound.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Projectors appeared in the late 1970s that featured the ability to play films with an optical soundtrack.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] The image-sound separation for the optical format was 22 frames.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] These were never popular in the English speaking world and are consequently very rare in those countries, but they did enjoy some popularity in the Far East and Europe mainly because optical prints were cheaper.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Sound prints in Super 8 were plentiful and considering that they were very expensive by modern-day standards, sold in appreciable quantities.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] A two-reel print (running approximately 17 minutes) cost around $50 with feature films costing at least $150-plus.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] A few prints were also released with stereo sound.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] In Europe, optical prints were also popular and were appreciated for their often superior sound quality.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] In theory, magnetic prints should have been superior, but Super 8 magnetic prints were often poorly recorded after the picture was processed, due to high-speed, mass production techniques.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] An optical track, on the other hand, could be printed at the same time as the image and in equivalent quality.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Another version of Super 8 film, Single-8, was produced by Fuji in Japan.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Introduced in 1965 as an alternative to the Kodak Super 8 format, it had the same final film dimensions but with a different cassette.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Unlike the co-axial design of Super 8, the Single 8 cartridge featured one spool above the other.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Single 8's film format being identical to Super 8 means that everything written above regarding projectors for Super 8 applies equally to Single 8.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Cameras also appeared for the Single 8 system that were capable of directly recording to pre-striped film which was presented in an oversize Single-8 cartridge which provided access for the camera's sound recording head in a similar manner to Super 8.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] The only difference was that film manufacturers initially had to manufacture the film with a rebated area for the sound stripe.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] This was because the pressure plate ensuring good film registration was part of the camera and not the cartridge.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] The sound film had to be the same overall thickness as silent film which the camera could also accept.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Although the rebated stock was more expensive to manufacture, a balance stripe on the opposite side of the film was rendered unnecessary and offset the cost.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Fuji later developed a thinner film that did not require rebating, but the balance stripe was required because the thickness of the sound stripe was almost the same as the film base.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] A number of camera companies offered single-width 8 mm film in magazines or spools, but the format faded when Kodak introduced Kodachrome, as this was only available in the Double 8 mm format.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] The first single-run 8 mm film was offered in 1935 with a Bell & Howell movie camera Filmo 127-A called Straight Eight.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Single-width 8 mm film revived in the United States by Bolsey-8 in 1956 and continued for some time outside the United States, with Germany Agfa Movex 8 between 1937 and 1950s and Soviet Union KOMZ Ekran movie cameras and Svema offering reversal film in 1960s.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Introduced in 2011 by Nicholas Kovats and implemented by Jean-Louis Seguin, this format uses Standard 8 film in a modified Bolex (H16 or H8) camera.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Similar to the Techniscope cameras of the 1960s, UltraPan 8 achieves wider aspect ratios generally reserved for camera systems with anamorphic lenses through manipulating film negative exposure instead of light capture.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] The area of film exposed per frame is 10.52 mm × 3.75 mm, having an aspect ratio of 2.8:1.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] There are effectively two UP8 frames for every one 16 mm frame.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] The design means there is no waste of film emulsion for the targeted aspect ratio.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] Earlier versions of this general idea date from the 1950s and exactly the same design occurs in implementations of the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:ken-burns/8-mm-film] The current implementation of the idea gains impetus from the relative ease with which digital delivery systems can handle what would otherwise have required, in the past, either a dedicated mechanical projector or the transfer to another film format for which projectors were already available.
[src:ken-burns/a-chef-s-life] Both Cynthia Hill and Vivian Howard grew up in Lenoir County, North Carolina, Hill in Pink Hill and Howard in Deep Run.
[src:ken-burns/a-chef-s-life] Vivian Howard and Cynthia Hill's younger sister were friends growing up.
[src:ken-burns/a-chef-s-life] Both Hill and Howard left their small, rural communities and returned again years later, Vivian to open Chef & the Farmer, and Cynthia to focus on southern storytelling.
[src:ken-burns/a-chef-s-life] The show won a Peabody Award on April 2, 2014 and a Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Culinary Program on April 26, 2018.
[src:ken-burns/a-chef-s-life] The show was nominated for two other Daytime Emmys in 2018: Outstanding Culinary Host and Outstanding Directing.
[src:ken-burns/a-chef-s-life] The show was also nominated for a Daytime Emmy in 2015 for Outstanding Single Camera Photography and was a 2014 James Beard broadcast award finalist.
[src:ken-burns/a-chef-s-life] Howard is working on a new show for PBS called *South By Somewhere*, which will consist of six, one-hour episodes.
[src:ken-burns/a-chef-s-life] As of 2015, the show was broadcast in 96% of the United States and each episode had 2.5 million viewers.
[src:ken-burns/a-chef-s-life] The first season of *A Chef's Life* consisted of 13 episodes.
[src:ken-burns/a-chef-s-life] The second season of "A Chef's Life consisted of 14 episodes and one hour-long holiday special.
[src:ken-burns/a-chef-s-life] The third season of "A Chef's Life consisted of 13 episodes.
[src:ken-burns/a-chef-s-life] Jill Warren Lucas from *Indy Week* praised the show.
[src:ken-burns/a-chef-s-life] A 2018 Jezebel article titled "The Future of Food TV Is Female" parallels Samin Nosrat's Netflix show *Salt Fat Acid Heat* to Vivian Howard's PBS series *A Chef's Life*.
[src:ken-burns/a-chef-s-life] Writer Megan Reynolds acknowledges the two shows' similarities by saying: "What differentiates Nosrat and Howard's shows from the men-hosted series is, of course, that they are women and are cleverly using their womanhood to subvert the expectations of what food television can and should be like.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] As she had begun to do in *Caged Bird*, and continued throughout her series, Angelou upheld the long tradition of African-American autobiography.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] At the same time she made a deliberate attempt to challenge the usual structure of the autobiography by critiquing, changing, and expanding the genre.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Most reviewers agreed that the book was made up of a series of vignettes.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] By the time *Song* was written in 2002, sixteen years after her previous autobiography, Angelou had experienced great fame and recognition as an author and poet.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] She recited her poem "On the Pulse of Morning" at the inauguration of President Bill Clinton in 1993, becoming the first poet to make an inaugural recitation since Robert Frost at John F.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] She had become recognized and highly respected as a spokesperson for Blacks and women.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Angelou was, as scholar Joanne Braxton has stated, "without a doubt, ...
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] America's most visible black woman autobiographer".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] She had also become, as reviewer Richard Long stated, "a major autobiographical voice of the time".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] The title of *Song* was based upon the same poem, by African-American poet Paul Laurence Dunbar, the basis of her first autobiography.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Like Angelou's other autobiographies, the book was greeted with both praise and disappointment, although reviews were generally positive.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Reviewers praised Angelou for "the culmination of a unique autobiographical achievement", while others criticized her for coming across as "smug".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] The 2002 spoken word album by the same name, based on the book, received a Grammy Award for Best Spoken Word Album in 2003.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] By 2002, when *Song* was published, Angelou had become recognized and highly respected as a spokesperson for Blacks and women.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] She was, as scholar Joanne Braxton has stated, "without a doubt, ...
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] She had also become "a major autobiographical voice of the time".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Angelou was one of the first African-American female writers to publicly discuss her personal life, and one of the first to use herself as a central character in her books.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Writer Julian Mayfield, who called her first autobiography "a work of art that eludes description", stated that Angelou's series set a precedent not only for other Black women writers, but for the genre of autobiography as a whole.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Als called Angelou one of the "pioneers of self-exposure", willing to focus honestly on the more negative aspects of her personality and choices.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] For example, while Angelou was composing her second autobiography, *Gather Together in My Name*, she was concerned about how her readers would react to her disclosure that she had been a prostitute.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Her husband Paul Du Feu talked her into publishing the book by encouraging her to "tell the truth as a writer" and to "be honest about it".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] *Song* took 16 years to write because it was painful to relive the events she described, including the assassinations of Malcolm X and Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] She did not celebrate her birthday, April 4, for many years because it was also the anniversary of King's death, choosing instead to send his widow Coretta Scott King flowers.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Although *Song* was considered the final installment in her series of autobiographies, Angelou continued writing about her life story through essays, and at the age of 85, published her seventh autobiography *Mom & Me & Mom* (2013), which focused on her relationship with her mother.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] The spoken word album based on *Song* and narrated by Angelou received a Grammy Award for Best Spoken Word Album in 2003.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Angelou returned to the same poem she based the title of *Caged Bird* upon for the title of *A Song Flung Up to Heaven,* from the third stanza of the Paul Laurence Dunbar poem "Sympathy".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Along with Shakespeare, Angelou has credited Dunbar with forming her "writing ambition".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] The caged bird, a symbol for the chained slave, is an image Angelou uses throughout all her writings.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] She postpones meeting with Malcolm X for a month and visits her mother and brother in San Francisco.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Malcolm X is assassinated two days later.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Devastated and grief-stricken, she moves to Hawaii to be near her brother and to resume her singing and performing career, which she had given up before leaving for Africa several years earlier.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] She realizes, after seeing Della Reese perform, that she lacks the desire, commitment, and talent to be a singer.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] She instead returns to her writing career, but this time in Los Angeles instead of in New York City as she had earlier in her life.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] To earn extra money, Angelou becomes a market researcher in Watts and gets to know the neighborhood and its people.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] She witnesses the 1965 Watts Riots, knowing that doing so could lead to her arrest, and she is genuinely disappointed that it does not.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] At one point, Angelou's lover from Ghana, whom she calls "the African", arrives in Los Angeles to take her back to Accra.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Angelou enlists the aid of her mother and brother; they come to her rescue once again by diverting the African first to Mexico and then back to Ghana.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Guy, during a visit to his grandmother in San Francisco, gets into another car accident, similar to what happened before he began college in Ghana.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] His maturity is striking to his mother, and she leaves him in the care of his grandmother.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Angelou returns to New York, where she dedicates herself to her writing and renews many of the friendships made there in the past.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] She also describes her personal and professional relationships with Ruby Dee, Ossie Davis, Beah Richards, and Frank Silvera.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Martin Luther King Jr. asks her to travel around the country promoting the Southern Christian Leadership Conference.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] She agrees, but "postpones again", and he is assassinated on her 40th birthday.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Again devastated, she isolates herself until invited to a dinner party also attended by her friend James Baldwin and cartoonist Jules Feiffer and his wife Judy.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Judy Feiffer, inspired by Angelou's tales about her childhood, contacts editor Robert Loomis, who challenges Angelou to write her autobiography as literature.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Starting with *Caged Bird*, Angelou made a deliberate attempt while writing all her autobiographies, including *Song*, to challenge the usual structure of the autobiography by critiquing, changing, and expanding the genre.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Her use of fiction-writing techniques such as dialogue, characterization, and thematic development has often led reviewers to categorize her books as autobiographical fiction.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Angelou stated in a 1989 interview that she was the only "serious" writer to choose the genre to express herself.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] As critic Susan Gilbert stated, Angelou was reporting not one person's story, but the collective's.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Cudjoe agreed, and viewed Angelou as representative of the convention in African-American autobiography as a public gesture that spoke for an entire group of people.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Angelou's editor Robert Loomis was able to dare her into writing *Caged Bird* by challenging her to write an autobiography that could be considered "high art", which she continued throughout her series, including her final autobiography.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Angelou's autobiographies conform to the genre's standard structure: they were written by a single author, they were chronological, and they contained elements of character, technique, and theme.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] In a 1983 interview with African-American literature critic Claudia Tate, Angelou called her books autobiographies.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] When speaking of her unique use of the genre, Angelou acknowledged that she has followed the slave narrative tradition of "speaking in the first-person singular talking about the first-person plural, always saying I meaning 'we'".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Washington agreed, and stated that *A Song Flung Up to Heaven* "offers a glimpse into the life of a literary icon in the making" influenced by historical events and personalities such as Malcolm X, Martin Luther King Jr., and James Baldwin.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Angelou recognized that there were fictional aspects to all her books; she tended to "diverge from the conventional notion of autobiography as truth".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Her approach paralleled the conventions of many African-American autobiographies written during the abolitionist period in the U.S., when truth was often censored for purposes of self-protection.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Hagen has placed Angelou in the long tradition of African-American autobiography, but insisted that she has created a unique interpretation of the autobiographical form.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] In a 1998 interview with journalist George Plimpton, Angelou discussed her writing process, and "the sometimes slippery notion of truth in nonfiction" and memoirs.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] When asked if she changed the truth to improve her story, she stated, "Sometimes I make a diameter from a composite of three or four people, because the essence in only one person is not sufficiently strong to be written about".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Although Angelou has never admitted to changing the facts in her stories, she has used these facts to make an impact with the reader.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] As Hagen stated, "One can assume that 'the essence of the data' is present in Angelou's work".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Hagen also stated that Angelou "fictionalizes, to enhance interest".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Angelou's long-time editor, Robert Loomis, agreed, stating that she could rewrite any of her books by changing the order of her facts to make a different impact on the reader.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Many reviewers appreciated what *Kirkus Reviews* called Angelou's "nice structural turn" of framing *Song* with two assassinations.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Paula Friedman of *The New York Times Book Review* appreciated Angelou's "occasions of critical self-assessment and modesty" not present in many other autobiographies.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Patricia Elam of *The New Crisis* agreed, stating that there is much to admire both about the book and about the "large life", full of tension, laughter, and love, it describes.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Elam also called *Song* "a spirit-moving work that describes Angelou's journey through an authentic and artistic life".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Reviewer Margaret Busby, who saw this book "not so much an ending as a beginning", called *Song* "the culmination of a unique autobiographical achievement, a glorious celebration of indomitable spirit".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Like other reviewers, Busby considered *Song* a series of "beautifully crafted vignettes" and found the book concise and readable.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Scholar John McWhorter did not look at Angelou's use of vignettes as positively, and stated that all of her books were short, divided into "ever shorter" chapters as her series progressed, and "sometimes seem written for children rather than adults".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] McWhorter recognized, however, that Angelou's precise prose and "striking and even jarring simplicity" was due to Angelou's purposes of depicting African-American culture in a positive way.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Busby also recognized Angelou's ability to find inspirational lessons from adversity, both nationally and personally, although the emphasis in this book was on the personal, especially her dilemmas as a mother and as a lover.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Amy Strong of *The Library Journal*, perhaps because Angelou's life during the time the book took place was full of more personal loss than conflict and struggle, considered *Song* less profound and intense than the previous books in Angelou's series.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] She predicted that *Song*′s direct and plainspoken style would be popular.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] *Publishers Weekly*, in its review of the book, agreed with Strong and saw "a certain resignation" in *Song*, instead of "the contentiousness" in Angelou's other autobiographies.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] The reviewer also stated that those who lived through the era Angelou described would appreciate her assessment of it, and that *Song* was "a story of tragedy and triumph, well stated and clearly stamped by her own unique blend of Afro-Americanism".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] The assassinations in *Song* provided the book with depth as Angelou described the events of her life, which would be "mere meanderings" if described by a less skilled writer.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] The reviewer was able to see Angelou's "gracious spirit" and found the book "satisfying", although he considered it a "sometimes flat account" that lacked "the spiritual tone of Angelou's essays, the openness of her poetry and the drama of her other autobiographies".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Both McWhorter and scholar Hilton Als found Angelou's writing throughout her series self-important.
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Als agreed, stating what made *Song* different from her preceding volumes is her "ever-increasing unreliability".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Als stated that Angelou, in her six autobiographies, "has given us ... the self-aggrandizing, homespun, and sometimes oddly prudish story of a black woman who, when faced with the trials of life, simply makes do".
[src:ken-burns/a-song-flung-up-to-heaven] Als believed that Angelou's essays, written in the 1990s, were a better culmination of her work as an autobiographer.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky, Lincoln was raised on the frontier.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was self-educated and became a lawyer, Illinois state legislator, and U.S. representative.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Angered by the Kansas–Nebraska Act of 1854, which opened the territories to slavery, he became a leader of the new Republican Party.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He reached a national audience in the 1858 Senate campaign debates against Stephen A.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election, becoming the first Republican president.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory prompted a majority of the slave states to begin seceding and form the Confederate States.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] A month after Lincoln assumed the presidency, Confederate forces attacked Fort Sumter, starting the Civil War.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] As a moderate Republican, Lincoln had to navigate conflicting political opinions from contentious factions during the war effort.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He closely supervised the Union's strategy and tactics, including the selection of generals and the implementation of a naval blockade of Southern ports.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He suspended the writ of *habeas corpus* in April 1861, an action that Chief Justice Roger Taney found in *Ex parte Merryman* that only Congress could do, and he averted war with Britain by defusing the *Trent* Affair.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 1, 1863, he issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared the slaves in the states "in rebellion" to be free.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 19, 1863, he delivered the Gettysburg Address, which became one of the most famous speeches in American history.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He promoted the Thirteenth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Constitution, which, in 1865, abolished chattel slavery.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Following his re-election in 1864, he sought to heal the war-torn nation through Reconstruction.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] On April 14, 1865, five days after the Confederate surrender at Appomattox, Lincoln was fatally shot by John Wilkes Booth at Ford's Theatre in Washington, D.C., becoming the first U.S. president to be assassinated.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln is remembered as a martyr and a national hero for his wartime leadership and for his efforts to preserve the Union and abolish slavery.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He is consistently ranked in both popular and scholarly polls as among the greatest presidents in American history.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky on February 12, 1809, Abraham Lincoln was raised on Sinking Spring Farm near Hodgenville, Kentucky.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] The captain was killed in a Native American raid in 1786.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] The family settled in Hardin County, Kentucky, in the early 1800s.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nancy is widely assumed to have been the daughter of Lucy Hanks.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy married on June 12, 1806, and moved to Elizabethtown, Kentucky.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] They had three children: Sarah, Abraham, and Thomas Jr., who died as an infant.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's father bought multiple farms in Kentucky but could not get clear property titles to any, losing hundreds of acres in legal disputes.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1816, the family moved to Indiana, where land titles were more reliable.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] They settled on a forested plot in Little Pigeon Creek Community.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Kentucky and Indiana, Thomas worked as a farmer, cabinetmaker, and carpenter.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] At various times, he owned farms, livestock, and town lots, appraised estates, and served on county patrols.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy were members of a Separate Baptist Church, a pious evangelical group whose members largely opposed slavery.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Overcoming financial challenges, Thomas obtained clear title to 80 acres (32 ha) in Little Pigeon Creek Community in 1827.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] On October 5, 1818, Nancy died from milk sickness, leaving 11-year-old Sarah in charge of the household, which included her father, 9-year-old Abraham, and Nancy's 19-year-old orphan cousin, Dennis Hanks.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas married Sarah Bush Johnston, a widow with three children of her own, on December 2, 1819.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became close to his stepmother and called her "Mama".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 20, 1828, Lincoln's sister died in childbirth, devastating him.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] His formal schooling was from itinerant teachers.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] It included two short stints in Kentucky, where he learned to read, but probably not to write.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] After moving to Indiana at age seven, he attended school only sporadically, for a total of less than 12 months by age 15.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nevertheless, he was an avid reader and maintained a lifelong interest in learning.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln was a teenager his father relied heavily on him for farmwork and for supplementary income, hiring the boy out to area farmers and pocketing the money, as was the custom at the time.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] When he was somewhat older, Lincoln and some friends took a job carrying goods by flatboat to New Orleans, Louisiana, where the slave markets, according to the historian Michael Burlingame, "would leave an indelible impression on him....
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In March 1830, fearing another milk-sickness outbreak, several members of the extended Lincoln family, including Abraham, moved west to Illinois and settled in Macon County.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became increasingly distant from Thomas, in part due to his father's lack of interest in education; he would later refuse to attend his father's deathbed or funeral in 1851.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Some historians, such as Michael Burlingame, identify Lincoln's first romantic interest as Ann Rutledge, a young woman also from Kentucky whom he met when he moved to New Salem, Illinois.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lewis Gannett disputes that the evidence supports a romantic relationship between the two.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] David Herbert Donald states that "How that friendship [between Lincoln and Rutledge] developed into a romance cannot be reconstructed from the record".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rutledge died on August 25, 1835, of typhoid fever.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln took her death very hard, sinking into a serious depression and contemplating suicide.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the early 1830s, Lincoln met Mary Owens from Kentucky.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Late in 1836, Lincoln agreed to marry Owens if she returned to New Salem.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Owens arrived that November and he courted her, but they both had second thoughts.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] On August 16, 1837, he wrote Owens a letter saying he would not blame her if she ended the relationship, and she declined to marry him.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1839, Lincoln met Mary Todd in Springfield, Illinois, and the following year they became engaged.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] She was a daughter of Robert Smith Todd, a wealthy lawyer and businessman in Lexington, Kentucky.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln initially broke off the engagement in early 1841, but the two were reconciled and married on November 4, 1842.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1844, the couple bought a house in Springfield near his law office.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] The marriage was turbulent; Mary was verbally abusive and at times physically violent towards her husband.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] The eldest, Robert Todd Lincoln, was born in 1843, and was the only child to live to maturity.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Edward Baker "Eddie" Lincoln, born in 1846, died February 1, 1850, probably of tuberculosis.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's third son, William Wallace "Willie" Lincoln, was born on December 21, 1850, and died of a fever at the White House on February 20, 1862.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] The youngest, Thomas "Tad" Lincoln, was born on April 4, 1853, and died of edema at age 18 on July 16, 1871.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln loved children, and the Lincolns were not considered to be strict with their own.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] The deaths of Eddie and Willie had profound effects on both parents.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln suffered from "melancholy", a condition now thought to be clinical depression.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1831, Lincoln's father moved the family to a new homestead in Coles County, Illinois, after which Abraham struck out on his own.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He made his home in New Salem, Illinois, for six years.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] During 1831 and 1832, Lincoln worked at a general store in New Salem.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He gained a reputation for strength and courage after winning a wrestling match with the leader of a group of ruffians known as the Clary's Grove boys.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1832, he declared his candidacy for the Illinois House of Representatives, though he interrupted his campaign to serve as a captain in the Illinois Militia during the Black Hawk War.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was elected the captain of his militia company but did not see combat.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his political campaigning, Lincoln advocated for navigational improvements on the Sangamon River.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He drew crowds as a raconteur, but he lacked name recognition, powerful friends, and money, and he lost the election.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln returned home from the war, he planned to become a blacksmith but instead purchased a New Salem general store in partnership with William Berry.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Because a license was required to sell customers alcoholic beverages, Berry obtained bartending licenses for Lincoln and himself, and in 1833 the Lincoln–Berry General Store became a tavern as well.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Burlingame wrote that Berry was "an undisciplined, hard-drinking fellow", and Lincoln "was too soft-hearted to deny anyone credit".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the economy was booming, the business struggled and went into debt, prompting Lincoln to sell his share.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served as New Salem's postmaster and later as county surveyor, but he continued his voracious reading and decided to become a lawyer.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rather than studying in the office of an established attorney, as was customary, Lincoln read law on his own, borrowing legal texts, including Blackstone's *Commentaries* and Chitty's *Pleadings*, from attorney John Todd Stuart.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He later said of his legal education that he "studied with nobody." He was bestowed an honorary degree of Doctor of Laws by Columbia University in 1861.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Lincoln's second state house campaign in 1834, as a supporter of Whig Party leader Henry Clay, he finished second among thirteen candidates running for four places.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln echoed Clay's support for the American Colonization Society, which advocated abolition in conjunction with settling freed slaves in Liberia.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Whigs also favored economic modernization in banking, tariffs to fund internal improvements such as railroads, and urbanization.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served four terms in the Illinois House of Representatives for Sangamon County.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this role, he championed construction of the Illinois and Michigan Canal.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln voted to expand suffrage beyond White landowners to all White men.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the chartering of the Illinois State Bank, and also led a successful campaign for moving the state capital from Vandalia to Springfield.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 27, 1838, Lincoln delivered an address at the Lyceum in Springfield, after the murder of the anti-slavery newspaper editor Elijah Parish Lovejoy.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this ostensibly non-partisan speech, Lincoln attacked Stephen A.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas and the Democratic Party, who the Whigs argued were supporting "mobocracy".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] His speech also attacked anti-abolitionism and racial bigotry.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was criticized in the press for a planned duel with James Shields, whom he had ridiculed in letters published under the name "Aunt Rebecca".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the duel did not take place, Burlingame noted that "the affair embarrassed Lincoln terribly".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1843, Lincoln sought the Whig nomination for Illinois's 7th district seat in the U.S.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Hardin was the winning candidate, though Lincoln convinced the party convention to limit Hardin to one term.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln not only gained the nomination in 1846, but also won the election.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] The only Whig in the Illinois delegation, he was assigned to the Committee on Post Office and Post Roads and the Committee on Expenditures in the War Department.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Giddings on a bill to abolish slavery in the District of Columbia, but dropped the bill when it failed to attract support from most other Whigs.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln spoke against the Mexican–American War (1846–1848), for which he said President James K.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk had "some strong motive ... to involve the two countries in a war, and trusting to escape scrutiny, by fixing the public gaze upon the exceeding brightness of military glory—that attractive rainbow, that rises in showers of blood".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the Wilmot Proviso, a failed 1846 proposal to ban slavery in any U.S. territory won from Mexico.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk insisted that Mexican soldiers had begun the war by "invading the territory of the State of Texas ... and shedding the blood of our citizens on our own soil".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his 1847 "spot resolutions", Lincoln rhetorically demanded that Polk tell Congress the exact "spot" where this occurred, but the Polk administration did not respond.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] His approach and rhetoric cost Lincoln political support in his district, and newspapers derisively nicknamed him "spotty Lincoln".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln had pledged in 1846 to serve only one term in the House.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the 1848 Whig National Convention, he initially supported Henry Clay and was among the leaders of the Illinois delegation backing Clay, voting for him on the early ballots.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] When it became clear that Clay could not secure the nomination, Lincoln joined other Whigs in shifting support to Zachary Taylor, who won the party's nomination and the presidency in 1848.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Taylor won, Lincoln hoped in vain to be appointed commissioner of the United States General Land Office.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] The administration offered to appoint him secretary of the Oregon Territory instead.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] This would have disrupted his legal and political career in Illinois, so he declined and resumed his law practice.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was admitted to the Illinois bar on September 9, 1836.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He moved to Springfield and began to practice law under John T.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He partnered for several years with Stephen T.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Logan and, in 1844, began his practice with William Herndon.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Springfield practice, according to Donald, Lincoln handled "virtually every kind of business that could come before a prairie lawyer".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He dealt with many transportation cases in the midst of the nation's western expansion, particularly river barge conflicts under the new railroad bridges.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1849 he received a patent for a flotation device for the movement of riverboats in shallow water and Lincoln initially favored riverboat legal interests, but he represented whoever hired him.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He represented a bridge company against a riverboat company in *Hurd v.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rock Island Bridge Company*, a landmark case involving a canal boat that sank after hitting a bridge.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] His patent was never commercialized, but it made Lincoln the only president to hold a patent.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln appeared before the Illinois Supreme Court in 411 cases.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] From 1853 to 1860, one of his largest clients was the Illinois Central Railroad, which Lincoln successfully sued to recover his legal fees.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln represented William "Duff" Armstrong in his 1858 trial for the murder of James Preston Metzker.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] The case is famous for Lincoln's use of a fact established by judicial notice to challenge the credibility of an eyewitness.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] After a witness testified to seeing the crime in the moonlight, Lincoln produced a *Farmers' Almanac* showing the Moon was at a low angle, drastically reducing visibility.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In an 1859 murder case, he defended "Peachy" Quinn Harrison, the grandson of Peter Cartwright, Lincoln's political opponent.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Harrison was charged with the murder of Greek Crafton who, according to Cartwright, said as he lay dying that he had "brought it upon myself" and that he forgave Harrison.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln angrily protested the judge's initial decision to exclude Cartwright's claim as hearsay.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln argued that the testimony involved a dying declaration and so was not subject to the hearsay rule.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Instead of holding Lincoln in contempt of court as expected, the judge, a Democrat, admitted the testimony into evidence, resulting in Harrison's acquittal.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Compromise of 1850 failed to alleviate tensions over slavery between the slave-holding South and the free North.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the slavery debate in the Nebraska and Kansas territories became particularly acrimonious, Illinois Senator Stephen A.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas proposed popular sovereignty as a compromise; the measure would allow the electorate of each territory to decide the status of slavery.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] The legislation alarmed many Northerners, who sought to prevent the spread of slavery, but Douglas's Kansas–Nebraska Act narrowly passed Congress in May 1854.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's Peoria Speech of October 1854, in which he declared his opposition to slavery, was one of an estimated 175 speeches he delivered in the next six years on the topic of excluding slavery from the territories.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's attacks on the Kansas–Nebraska Act marked his return to political life.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nationally, the Whigs were irreparably split by the Kansas–Nebraska Act and other ineffective efforts to compromise on the slavery issue.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Reflecting on the demise of his party, Lincoln wrote in 1855, "I think I am a whig; but others say there are no whigs, and that I am an abolitionist....
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] I now do no more than oppose the *extension* of slavery." The new Republican Party was formed as a northern party dedicated to anti-slavery, drawing from the anti-slavery wing of the Whig Party and combining Free Soil, Liberty, and anti-slavery Democratic Party members.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln resisted early Republican entreaties, fearing that the new party would become a platform for extreme abolitionists.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln held out hope for rejuvenating the Whigs, though he lamented his party's growing closeness with the nativist Know Nothing movement.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1854, Lincoln was elected to the Illinois legislature, but before the term began he declined to take his seat so that he would be eligible to run in the upcoming U.S.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] At that time, senators were elected by state legislatures.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] After leading in the first six rounds of voting, Lincoln was unable to obtain a majority.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln instructed his backers to vote for Lyman Trumbull, an anti-slavery Democrat who had received few votes in the earlier ballots.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's decision to withdraw enabled his Whig supporters and Trumbull's anti-slavery Democrats to combine and defeat the mainstream Democratic candidate, Joel Aldrich Matteson.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Violent political confrontations in Kansas continued, and opposition to the Kansas–Nebraska Act remained strong throughout the North.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the 1856 elections approached, Lincoln joined the Republicans and attended the Bloomington Convention, where the Illinois Republican Party was established.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] The convention platform endorsed Congress's right to regulate slavery in the territories and backed the admission of Kansas as a free state.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln gave the final speech of the convention, calling for the preservation of the Union.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the June 1856 Republican National Convention, Lincoln received support to run as vice president, but the party put forward a ticket of John C.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Frémont and William Dayton, which Lincoln supported throughout Illinois.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Democrats nominated James Buchanan and the Know Nothings nominated Millard Fillmore.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Buchanan prevailed, while Republican William Henry Bissell won election as Governor of Illinois, and Lincoln became a leading Republican in Illinois.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Dred Scott was a slave whose master took him from a slave state to a territory that was free as a result of the Missouri Compromise.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Scott was returned to the slave state, he petitioned a federal court for his freedom.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] His petition was denied in *Dred Scott v.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Taney wrote in his opinion that the Missouri Compromise was unconstitutional because it infringed on slave owners' property rights by prohibiting them from bringing their slaves into the territories.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] While many Democrats hoped that *Dred Scott* would end the dispute over slavery in the territories, the decision sparked further outrage in the North.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln denounced it as the product of a conspiracy of Democrats to support the Slave Power.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He argued that the decision was at variance with the Declaration of Independence, which stated that "all men are created equal ... with certain unalienable rights", among them "life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1858, Douglas was up for re-election in the U.S.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Senate, and Lincoln hoped to defeat him.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the party felt that a former Whig should be nominated in 1858, and Lincoln's 1856 campaigning and support of Trumbull had earned him a favor.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] For the first time, Illinois Republicans held a convention to agree upon a Senate candidate, and Lincoln won the nomination with little opposition.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln accepted the nomination with great enthusiasm and zeal.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] The speech created a stark image of the danger of disunion.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Senate campaign featured seven debates between Lincoln and Douglas; they had an atmosphere akin to a prizefight and drew thousands.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln warned that the Slave Power was threatening the values of republicanism, and he accused Douglas of distorting Jefferson's premise that all men are created equal.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Freeport Doctrine, Douglas argued that, despite the *Dred Scott* decision, which he claimed to support, local settlers, under popular sovereignty, should be free to choose whether to allow slavery in their territory.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He accused Lincoln of having joined the abolitionists.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though the Republican legislative candidates won more popular votes, the Democrats won more seats, and the legislature re-elected Douglas.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] However, Lincoln's articulation of the issues had given him a national political presence.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the aftermath of the 1858 election, newspapers frequently mentioned Lincoln as a potential Republican presidential candidate.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] While Lincoln was popular in the Midwest, he lacked support in the Northeast and was unsure whether to seek the office.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In January 1860, Lincoln told a group of political allies that he would accept the presidential nomination if offered and, in the following months, William O.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Stoddard's *Central Illinois Gazette*, the *Chicago Press & Tribune*, and other local papers endorsed his candidacy.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In February 1860, Henry Ward Beecher invited Lincoln to address his congregation at Plymouth Church in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln agreed, but the venue shifted to Cooper Union in Manhattan.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the audience thought he appeared awkward and even ugly.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] But Lincoln demonstrated intellectual leadership, which brought him into contention for the presidency.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Journalist Noah Brooks reported, "No man ever before made such an impression on his first appeal to a New York audience".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Historian David Herbert Donald described the speech as "a superb political move for an unannounced presidential aspirant." In response to an inquiry about his ambitions, Lincoln said, "The taste *is* in my mouth a little".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 9–10, 1860, the Illinois Republican State Convention was held in Decatur.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Exploiting his embellished frontier legend of clearing land and splitting fence rails, Lincoln's supporters promoted him as "The Rail Candidate".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 18 at the Republican National Convention in Chicago, Lincoln won the nomination on the third ballot.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] A former Democrat, Hannibal Hamlin of Maine, was nominated for vice president to balance the ticket.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Throughout the 1850s, Lincoln had doubted the prospects of civil war, and his supporters rejected claims that his election would incite secession.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Douglas was selected as the candidate of the Northern Democrats, delegates from the Southern slave states elected incumbent Vice President John C.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] A group of former Whigs and Know Nothings formed the Constitutional Union Party and nominated John Bell of Tennessee.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln and Douglas competed for votes in the North, while Bell and Breckinridge found support primarily in the South.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] A nationwide militaristic Republican youth organization, the Wide Awakes, "turned it into one of the most excited elections in American history" and "triggered massive popular enthusiasm", according to the political historian Jon Grinspan.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] People of the Northern states knew the Southern states would vote against Lincoln and rallied supporters for him.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] As Douglas and the other candidates campaigned, Lincoln gave no speeches, relying on the enthusiasm of the Republican Party.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Republican speakers emphasized Lincoln's childhood poverty to demonstrate the power of "free labor", which allowed a common farm boy to work his way to the top by his own efforts.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though he did not make public appearances, many sought to visit and write to Lincoln.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the runup to the election, he took an office in the Illinois state capitol to deal with the influx of attention.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] He also hired John George Nicolay as his personal secretary, who would remain in that role during the presidency.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 6, 1860, Lincoln was elected as the first Republican president.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory was entirely due to his support in the North and West.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] No ballots were cast for him in 10 of the 15 Southern slave states.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln received 1,866,452 votes, or 39.8 percent of the total in a four-way race, carrying the free Northern states, as well as California and Oregon, and winning the electoral vote decisively.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] above the rotunda still under construction.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] following Lincoln's first inauguration portended imminent hostilities.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Lincoln's election, secessionists implemented plans to leave the Union before he took office in March 1861.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] On December 20, 1860, South Carolina adopted an ordinance of secession; by February 1, 1861, Florida, Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas had followed.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Six of these states declared themselves to be a sovereign nation, the Confederate States of America, selecting Jefferson Davis as its provisional president.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The upper South and border states (Delaware, Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky, Missouri, and Arkansas) initially rejected the secessionist appeal.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] President Buchanan and President-elect Lincoln refused to recognize the Confederacy, declaring secession illegal.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 11, 1861, Lincoln gave a particularly emotional farewell address upon leaving Springfield for Washington.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and the Republicans rejected the proposed Crittenden Compromise as contrary to the party's platform of free-soil in the territories.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln said, "I will suffer death before I consent ... to any concession or compromise which looks like buying the privilege to take possession of this government to which we have a constitutional right".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln supported the Corwin Amendment to the U.S.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Constitution, which would have protected slavery in states where it already existed.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The amendment passed Congress and was awaiting ratification by the required three-fourths of the states when Southern states began to secede.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] On March 4, 1861, in his first inaugural address, Lincoln said that, because he held "such a provision to now be implied constitutional law, I have no objection to its being made express, and irrevocable".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Due to secessionist plots, careful attention was paid to Lincoln's security and the train he took to Washington.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president-elect evaded suspected assassins in Baltimore.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] He traveled in disguise, wearing a soft felt hat instead of his customary stovepipe hat and draping an overcoat over his shoulders while hunching to conceal his height.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 23, 1861, he arrived in Washington, D.C., which was placed under military guard.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many in the opposition press criticized his secretive journey; opposition newspapers mocked Lincoln with caricatures showing him sneaking into the capital.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president ended his address with an appeal to the people of the South: "We are not enemies, but friends....
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The mystic chords of memory, stretching from every battle-field, and patriot grave, to every living heart and hearthstone ... will yet swell the chorus of the Union, when again touched ... by the better angels of our nature".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Donald, the failure of the Peace Conference of 1861 to attract the attendance of seven of the Confederate states signaled that legislative compromise was not a practical expectation.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In selecting his cabinet, Lincoln chose the men he found the most competent, even when they had been his opponents for the presidency.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln commented on his thought process, "We need the strongest men of the party in the Cabinet.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] We needed to hold our own people together.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] I had looked the party over and concluded that these were the very strongest men.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Then I had no right to deprive the country of their services." Doris Kearns Goodwin described the group in her 2005 biography of Lincoln as a "team of rivals".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln named his main political opponent, William H.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln made five appointments to the Supreme Court.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Noah Haynes Swayne, a prominent corporate lawyer from Ohio, replaced John McLean after the latter's death in April 1861.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Samuel Freeman Miller, who replaced Peter V.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Daniel, was an avowed abolitionist and received widespread support from Iowa politicians.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] David Davis was Lincoln's campaign manager in 1860 and had served as a judge in the Illinois court circuit where Lincoln practiced.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democrat Stephen Johnson Field, a previous California Supreme Court justice, provided geographic and political balance.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Taney, Lincoln appointed his former secretary of the treasury, Salmon P.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Chase, to replace Taney as chief justice.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln believed Chase was an able jurist who would support Reconstruction legislation and that his appointment would unite the Republican Party.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April 1861, Major Robert Anderson, commander of Fort Sumter in Charleston, South Carolina, advised that he was nearly out of food.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] After considerable deliberation, Lincoln decided to send provisions; according to Michael Burlingame, he "could not be sure that his decision would precipitate a war, though he had good reason to believe that it might".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 12, 1861, Confederate forces fired on Union troops at Fort Sumter, starting the American Civil War.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The April 12 and 13 attack on Fort Sumter rallied the Northern public to see military action against the South as necessary to defend the nation.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 15, Lincoln called for 75,000 militiamen to recapture forts, protect Washington, and preserve the Union.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] This call forced states to choose whether to secede or to support the Union.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] North Carolina, Virginia, Tennessee, and Arkansas seceded.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the Northern states sent regiments south, on April 19 Baltimore mobs in control of the rail links attacked Union troops who were changing trains.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Local leaders' groups later burned critical rail bridges to the capital and the Army responded by arresting local Maryland officials.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln suspended the writ of *habeas corpus*, allowing arrests without formal charges.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Merryman, a Maryland officer arrested for hindering U.S. troop movements, successfully petitioned Supreme Court Chief Justice Taney to issue a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In an opinion titled *Ex parte Merryman*, Taney, not ruling on behalf of the Supreme Court, wrote that the Constitution authorized only Congress and not the president to suspend habeas corpus.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] But Lincoln engaged in nonacquiescence and persisted with the policy of suspension in select areas.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Under various suspensions, 15,000 civilians were detained without trial; several, including the anti-war Democrat Clement L.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Vallandigham, were tried in military courts for "treasonable" actions, which was condemned as an attack on free speech.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln took executive control of the war and shaped the Union military strategy.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] He responded to the unprecedented political and military crisis as commander-in-chief by exercising unprecedented authority.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] He expanded his war powers, imposed a naval blockade on Confederate ports, disbursed funds before appropriation by Congress, suspended *habeas corpus*, and arrested and imprisoned thousands of suspected Confederate sympathizers.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gained the support of Congress and the northern public for these actions.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also had to reinforce Union sympathies in the border slave states and keep the war from becoming an international conflict.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was clear from the outset that bipartisan support was essential to success, and that any compromise alienated factions in both political parties.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Copperheads (anti-war Democrats) criticized Lincoln for refusing to compromise on slavery; the Radical Republicans, who demanded harsh treatment against secession, criticized him for moving too slowly to abolish slavery.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] On August 6, 1861, Lincoln signed the Confiscation Act, which authorized judicial proceedings to confiscate and free slaves who were used to support the Confederates.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law had little practical effect, but it signaled political support for abolishing slavery.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's war strategy had two priorities: ensuring that Washington was well defended and conducting an aggressive war effort for a prompt, decisive victory.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Twice a week, Lincoln met with his cabinet.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Occasionally, Lincoln's wife, Mary, prevailed on him to take a carriage ride, concerned that he was working too hard.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, Lincoln selected civilian generals from varied political and ethnic backgrounds "to secure their and their constituents' support for the war effort and ensure that the war became a national struggle".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In January 1862, after complaints of inefficiency and profiteering in the War Department, Lincoln replaced Simon Cameron as secretary of war with Edwin Stanton.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stanton worked more often and more closely with Lincoln than did any other senior official.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Stanton's biographers Benjamin P.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Thomas and Harold Hyman, "Stanton and Lincoln virtually conducted the war together".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln saw the importance of Vicksburg for control of the Mississippi River valley and understood the necessity of defeating the enemy's army, rather than merely capturing territory.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In directing the Union's war strategy, Lincoln valued the advice of Winfield Scott, even after his retirement as Commanding General of the United States Army.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1861 Scott proposed the Anaconda Plan, which relied on port blockades and advancing down the Mississippi to subdue the South.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In June 1862, Lincoln made an unannounced visit to West Point, where he spent five hours consulting with Scott regarding the handling of the war.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Internationally, Lincoln wanted to forestall foreign military aid to the Confederacy.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] He relied on his combative Secretary of State William Seward while working closely with Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman Charles Sumner.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Navy illegally intercepted a British mail ship, the *RMS Trent*, on the high seas and seized two Confederate envoys.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although the North celebrated the seizure, Britain protested vehemently, and the Trent Affair threatened war between the Americans and the British.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ended the crisis by releasing the two diplomats.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union rout at Bull Run and Winfield Scott's retirement, Lincoln appointed George B.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, McClellan created defenses for Washington that were almost impregnable: 48 forts and batteries, with 480 guns manned by 7,200 artillerists.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] He spent months planning his Virginia Peninsula Campaign.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan's slow progress and excessive precautions frustrated Lincoln.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan, in turn, blamed the failure of the campaign on Lincoln's cautiousness in having reserved troops for the capital.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1862, Lincoln removed McClellan as general-in-chief; he elevated Henry Halleck to the post and appointed John Pope as head of the new Army of Virginia.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the summer of 1862 Pope was soundly defeated at the Second Battle of Bull Run, forcing him to retreat to Washington.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Soon after, the Army of Virginia was disbanded.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite his dissatisfaction with McClellan's failure to reinforce Pope, Lincoln restored him to command of all forces around Washington, which included both the Army of the Potomac and the remains of the Army of Virginia.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's forces crossed the Potomac River into Maryland, leading to the Battle of Antietam.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] This battle, a Union victory, was among the bloodiest in American history.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] A crisis of command occurred for Lincoln when McClellan then resisted the president's demand that he pursue Lee's withdrawing army, while Don Carlos Buell likewise refused orders to move the Army of the Ohio against rebel forces in eastern Tennessee.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln replaced Buell with William Rosecrans and McClellan with Ambrose Burnside; according to Donald, this was a "shrewd" political move as they were non-partisan—unlike McClellan, a Democrat.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Against presidential advice, Burnside launched an offensive across the Rappahannock River and was defeated by Lee at Fredericksburg in December.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Facing low morale and discontent among the troops, Lincoln replaced Burnside with Joseph Hooker.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hooker endured heavy casualties at the Battle of Chancellorsville in May, then resigned in June and was replaced by George Meade.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Meade followed Lee north into Pennsylvania and defeated him in the Gettysburg campaign but then failed to effectively block Lee's orderly retreat to Virginia, despite Lincoln's demands.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant captured Vicksburg and gained control of the Mississippi River.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In May 1863, Lincoln issued the Lieber Code, which governed wartime conduct of the Union Army, defining command responsibility for war crimes and crimes against humanity.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two Union generals had issued emancipation orders in 1861 and 1862, but Lincoln overrode both: he found that the decision to emancipate was not within the generals' power, and that it might induce loyal border states to secede.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, in June 1862, Congress passed an act banning slavery in all federal territories, which Lincoln signed.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In July, the Confiscation Act of 1862 was enacted, allowing the seizure of slaves from those disloyal to the United States.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] On July 22, 1862, Lincoln reviewed a draft of the Emancipation Proclamation with his cabinet.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Senator Willard Saulsbury Sr. criticized the proclamation, stating that it "would light their author to dishonor through all future generations".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] By contrast, Horace Greeley, editor of the *New-York Tribune*, in his public letter, "The Prayer of Twenty Millions", implored Lincoln to embrace emancipation.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Buttressed by news of the recent Union victory at Antietam, on September 22, 1862, Lincoln issued the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, which proclaimed that, on January 1, 1863, all persons held as slaves within any state still in rebellion would be free.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] On January 1, 1863, he issued the final Emancipation Proclamation, freeing the slaves in the ten states not then under Union control, exempting areas under such control.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] With the abolition of slavery in the rebel states now a military objective, Union armies advancing south enabled thousands to escape bondage.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Proclamation was immediately denounced by Copperheads, who advocated restoring the union by allowing slavery.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was also seen as a betrayal of his promise to Southern Unionists not to tamper with slavery; Emerson Etheridge, then Clerk of the House of Representatives, joined an unsuccessful plot to give the Democrats and Southern Unionists control of the House.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a result of the Proclamation, enlisting freedmen became official policy.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In a letter to Tennessee military governor Andrew Johnson, Lincoln wrote, "The bare sight of fifty thousand armed, and drilled black soldiers on the banks of the Mississippi would end the rebellion at once".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gave the dedication for the Gettysburg battlefield cemetery on November 19, 1863.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The address became the most quoted speech in American history.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Following Admiral David Farragut's capture of New Orleans in 1862, and after victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg, Lincoln proclaimed a national Thanksgiving holiday, to be celebrated on the final Thursday of November 1863.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's victories at the Battle of Shiloh and in the Vicksburg campaign impressed Lincoln.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Responding to criticism of Grant after Shiloh, Lincoln said, "I can't spare this man.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] He fights." Following Meade's failure to capture Lee's army after Gettysburg and after Grant's success at Chattanooga, Lincoln promoted Grant to commander of all Union armies.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln reacted to Union losses by mobilizing support throughout the North.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union forces targeted infrastructure—plantations, railroads, and bridges—to weaken the South's morale and fighting ability.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] While Lincoln sanctioned this approach, he emphasized the defeat of the Confederate armies over destruction for its own sake.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody Overland Campaign turned into a strategic success for the Union despite a number of setbacks.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] But the campaign was the bloodiest in American history: approximately 55,000 casualties on the Union side (including 7,600 deaths), compared to about 33,000 on the Confederate (including 4,200 deaths).
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's losses, although lower in absolute numbers, were proportionately higher (over 50%) than Grant's (about 45%).
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April, the Confederate government evacuated Richmond and Lincoln visited the conquered capital.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Amid the turmoil of military actions, on June 30, 1864, Lincoln signed into law the Yosemite Grant, which provided unprecedented federal protection for the area now known as Yosemite National Park.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and Secretary of the Treasury Salmon Chase faced a challenge in funding a wartime economy.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress quickly approved Lincoln's request to assemble an army, even increasing his proposed 400,000 soldiers to 500,000, but both Congress and Chase initially resisted raising taxes.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union defeat at the First Battle of Bull Run, which collapsed the bond market, Congress passed the Revenue Act of 1861.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] This act imposed the first U.S. federal income tax, creating a flat tax of three percent on annual incomes above $800 ($28,700 in current dollars).
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the average urban worker made approximately $600 per year, many were not required to pay income taxes.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also signed increases to the Morrill Tariff, which had become law in the final months of Buchanan's tenure.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] These tariffs raised import duties considerably and were designed both to increase revenue and to help manufacturers offset the burden of new taxes.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Throughout the war, Congress debated whether to raise additional revenue primarily by increasing tariff rates, which most strongly affected rural areas, or by increasing income taxes, which most affected wealthier individuals; the latter view proved more popular.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The revenue measures of 1861 proved inadequate for funding the war, forcing Congress to take further action.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In February 1862, Congress passed the Legal Tender Act, which authorized the minting of $150 million in "greenbacks"—the first banknotes issued by the U.S. government since the end of the American Revolution.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Greenbacks were not backed by gold or silver, but rather by the government's promise to honor their value.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, $450 million worth of greenbacks were in circulation.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress also passed the Revenue Act of 1862, which established an excise tax affecting nearly every commodity, as well as the first national inheritance tax.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] It also added a progressive tax structure to the federal income tax.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] To collect these taxes, Congress created the Office of the Commissioner of Internal Revenue.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite the new revenue measures, funding the war remained challenging.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The government continued to issue greenbacks and borrow large amounts of money, and the U.S. national debt grew from $65 million in 1860 to over $2 billion in 1866.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Revenue Act of 1864 represented a compromise between those who favored a more progressive tax structure and those who favored a flat tax.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] It established a five-percent tax on incomes above $600 and a ten-percent tax on incomes above $10,000, and it raised taxes on businesses.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early 1865, Congress reduced the threshold for ten-percent taxation to incomes above $5000.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, the income tax constituted about one-fifth of the federal government's revenue, though it was intended as a temporary wartime measure.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also took action against wartime fraud, signing into law the False Claims Act of 1863.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] This statute imposed penalties for false claims and made it possible for private citizens to file false-claim (*qui tam*) lawsuits on behalf of the U.S. government and share in the recovery.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hoping to stabilize the currency, Lincoln convinced Congress to pass the National Banking Act in 1863, established the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency to oversee "national banks," which were subject to federal, rather than state, regulation.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In return for investing a third of their capital in federal bonds, national banks were authorized to issue federal banknotes.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Congress imposed a tax on private banknotes in March 1865, federal banknotes became the dominant form of paper currency.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Other economic policies passed under Lincoln included the 1862 Homestead Act, which made millions of acres of government-held land in the West available for purchase at low cost.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The 1862 Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act provided government grants for agricultural colleges in each state.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Pacific Railway Acts of 1862 and 1864 granted federal support for the construction of the United States' first transcontinental railroad, which was completed in 1869.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the start of the war, Russia was the lone great power to support the Union, while the other European powers had varying degrees of sympathy for the Confederacy.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to the historian Dean Mahin, Lincoln had "limited familiarity with diplomatic practices" but exerted "substantial influence on U.S. diplomacy" as the Union attempted to avoid war with Britain and France.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln appointed diplomats to try to persuade European nations not to recognize the Confederacy.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policy succeeded: all foreign nations were officially neutral throughout the Civil War, with none recognizing the Confederacy.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some European leaders looked for ways to exploit the inability of the U.S. to enforce the Monroe Doctrine opposing European colonial intervention in the Americas: Spain invaded the Dominican Republic in 1861, while France established a puppet regime in Mexico.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, many in Europe also hoped for a quick end to the war, both for humanitarian reasons and because of the economic disruption it caused.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed", according to Don H.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union diplomats initially had to explain that the United States was not committed to ending slavery, and instead they argued that secession was unconstitutional.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Confederate spokesmen were more successful by ignoring slavery and instead focusing on their struggle for independence, their commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Confederacy's hope that cotton exports would compel European interference did not come to fruition, as Britain found alternative sources and maintained economic ties with the Union.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Though the issuance of the Emancipation Proclamation in January 1863 did not immediately end the possibility of European intervention, it rallied European public opinion to the Union by adding abolition as a Union war goal.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Any chance of a European intervention in the war ended with the Union victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg in July 1863, as European leaders came to believe that the Confederate cause was doomed.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Dole as commissioner of the Bureau of Indian Affairs and made "extensive use of Indian Service positions to reward political supporters", according to the historian Thomas Britten.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policies largely focused on assimilation of Native Americans and diminishing tribal landholdings, consistent with those of his predecessors, but his direct involvement in Native American affairs was unclear.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] His administration faced difficulties guarding Western settlers, railroads, and telegraph lines from Native American attacks.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Tensions arose with the Dakota people due to American treaty violations, unfair trading, and government practices that led to starvation.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In August 1862, the Dakota War broke out in Minnesota.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hundreds of settlers were killed and 30,000 were displaced from their homes.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some feared incorrectly that it might represent a Confederate conspiracy to start a war on the Northwestern frontier.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ordered thousands of paroled prisoners of war be sent to put down the uprising.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] When the Confederacy protested, Lincoln revoked the policy and none arrived in Minnesota.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln sent Pope as commander of the new Department of the Northwest.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Appointed as a state militia colonel, Henry Hastings Sibley eventually defeated the Dakota chief Little Crow at the Battle of Wood Lake.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] A war crimes trial led by Sibley sentenced 303 Dakota warriors to death; the legal scholar Carol Chomsky described the trial as "a study in military injustice" designed to "guarantee an unjust outcome".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln pardoned all but 39 of the condemned warriors, and, with one execution suspended, the remaining 38 were hanged in the largest mass execution in U.S. history.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congressman Alexander Ramsey told Lincoln in 1864 that he would have received more re-election support in Minnesota had he executed all 303 warriors.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln responded, "I could not afford to hang men for votes." Lincoln called for reform of federal Indian policy but prioritized the war and Reconstruction.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Changes were made in response to the Sand Creek Massacre of November 1864, prioritizing peaceful administration of Native affairs and condemning those encroaching on Native territory, but not until after Lincoln's death.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ran for re-election in 1864; the Democratic nominee was former general McClellan.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Republican Party selected Andrew Johnson, a War Democrat, as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] To broaden his coalition to include War Democrats as well as Republicans, Lincoln ran under the new label of the National Union Party.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody stalemates and Confederate victories such as the Battle of the Crater damaged Lincoln's re-election prospects, and many Republicans feared defeat.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln prepared a confidential memorandum pledging that, if he should lose the election, he would "co-operate with the President-elect, as to save the Union between the election and the inauguration; as he will have secured his election on such ground that he cannot possibly save it afterwards".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Victories at Atlanta in September and in the Shenandoah Valley in October turned public opinion, and Lincoln was re-elected with 55.1 percent of the popular vote as well as 212 electoral votes to McClellan's 21.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Grant continued to weaken Lee's forces, efforts to discuss peace began.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephens, the Confederate vice president, and two other Confederate officials met with Lincoln and Seward at Hampton Roads.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln refused to negotiate with the Confederacy as a coequal, and the only agreement reached at the meeting concerned the exchange of prisoners.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's second inauguration took place on March 4, 1865; historian Mark Noll places his second inaugural address "among the small handful of semi-sacred texts by which Americans conceive their place in the world"; it is inscribed in the Lincoln Memorial.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] A month later, on April 9, Lee surrendered to Grant at Appomattox, signaling the end of the war.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] It triggered a series of subsequent surrenders across the South—in North Carolina, Alabama, and the trans-Mississippi Theater—and finally at sea with the surrender of the CSS *Shenandoah* in November 1865.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Reconstruction began before the war's end, as Lincoln and his associates considered the reintegration of the nation, and the fates of Confederate leaders and freed slaves.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] When a general asked Lincoln how the defeated Confederates were to be treated, Lincoln replied, "Let 'em up easy"; he focused not on blame for the war but on rebuilding.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Determined to reunite the nation and not alienate the South, Lincoln urged that speedy elections under generous terms be held.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] His Amnesty Proclamation of December 8, 1863, offered pardons to those who had not held a Confederate civil office and had not mistreated Union prisoners, if they signed an oath of allegiance.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln led the moderates in Reconstruction policy and was opposed by the Radicals, under Thaddeus Stevens, Charles Sumner and Benjamin Wade, who otherwise remained Lincoln's allies.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Southern states fell, they needed leaders while their administrations were being restored.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Tennessee and Arkansas, Lincoln appointed Andrew Johnson and Frederick Steele, respectively, as military governors.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Louisiana, Lincoln ordered Nathaniel P.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Banks to promote a plan that would reestablish statehood when 10 percent of the voters agreed, but only if the reconstructed states abolished slavery.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democratic opponents accused Lincoln of using the plan to ensure his and the Republicans' political aspirations.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals denounced his policy as too lenient and passed their own plan, the 1864 Wade–Davis Bill, but Lincoln pocket-vetoed it.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals retaliated by refusing to seat elected representatives from Louisiana, Arkansas, and Tennessee.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] After implementing the Emancipation Proclamation, Lincoln increased pressure on Congress to outlaw slavery nationwide with a constitutional amendment.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] By December 1863 an amendment was brought to Congress.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Senate passed it on April 8, 1864, but the first vote in the House of Representatives fell short of the required two-thirds majority.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Passage became part of Lincoln's re-election platform, and after his re-election, the second attempt in the House passed on January 31, 1865.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] After ratification by three-fourths of the states in December 1865, it became the Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution, abolishing "slavery [and] involuntary servitude, except as a punishment for crime".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln announced a Reconstruction plan that involved short-term military administration, pending readmission under the control of southern Unionists.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] He also signed Senator Charles Sumner's Freedmen's Bureau bill that set up a temporary federal agency designed to meet the immediate needs of former slaves.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law opened land for a lease of three years with the ability for the freedmen to purchase title.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Eric Foner argues that "Lincoln did not see Reconstruction as an opportunity for a sweeping political and social revolution beyond emancipation.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] He had long made clear his opposition to the confiscation and redistribution of land." However, the Lincoln scholar Phillip S.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Paludan suggests that at the end of his life Lincoln was moving towards a more radical position, particularly with regards to freedmen's rights.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Wilkes Booth was a well-known actor and a Confederate spy from Maryland; although he never joined the Confederate army, he had contacts within the Confederate secret service.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] After attending Lincoln's last public address, on April 11, 1865, in which Lincoln stated his preference that the franchise be conferred on some Black men, specifically "on the very intelligent, and on those who serve our cause as soldiers", Booth plotted to assassinate the President.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] When Booth learned of the Lincolns' intent to attend a play with Grant, he planned to assassinate Lincoln and Grant at Ford's Theatre.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and his wife attended the play *Our American Cousin* on the evening of April 14.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the last minute, Grant decided to go to New Jersey to visit his children instead.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] At 10:15 pm, Booth entered Lincoln's theater box, crept up from behind, and fired at the back of Lincoln's head, mortally wounding him.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's guest, Major Henry Rathbone, momentarily grappled with Booth, but Booth stabbed him and escaped.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] After being attended by Charles Leale and two other doctors, Lincoln was taken across the street to Petersen House.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] He remained in a coma for nine hours and died at 7:22 am on April 15.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was wrapped in a flag and placed in a coffin, which was loaded into a hearse and escorted to the White House by Union soldiers.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Johnson was sworn in as president later that day.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two weeks later, Booth was located, shot, and killed at a farm in Virginia by Sergeant Boston Corbett.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] From April 19 to 20, Lincoln lay in state, first in the White House and then in the Capitol rotunda.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The caskets containing Lincoln's body and the body of his third son Willie then traveled for two weeks on a funeral train following a circuitous route from Washington D.C. to Springfield, Illinois, stopping at several cities for memorials attended by hundreds of thousands.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many others gathered along the tracks as the train passed with bands, bonfires, and hymn singing or in silent grief.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Historians emphasized the widespread shock and sorrow, but noted that some who had hated Lincoln celebrated his death.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Walt Whitman composed four elegies to Lincoln, including "When Lilacs Last in the Dooryard Bloom'd" and "O Captain!
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was buried at Oak Ridge Cemetery in Springfield and now lies within the Lincoln Tomb.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln redefined the political philosophy of republicanism in the United States.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Because the Declaration of Independence says that all men have an unalienable right to life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness, he called it the "sheet anchor" of republicanism, at a time when the Constitution was the focus of most political discourse.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] He presented the Declaration as establishing equality as a foundational principle for the United States, which had a significant impact on social and political movements in the U.S. into the 20th century.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a Whig activist, Lincoln was a spokesman for business interests, favoring high tariffs, banks, infrastructure improvements, and railroads, in opposition to Jacksonian democrats.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Nevertheless, Lincoln admired Andrew Jackson's steeliness and patriotism, and adopted the Jacksonian "belief in the common man".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a young man, Lincoln was a religious skeptic.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, he was deeply familiar with the Bible; throughout his public career, he often quoted scripture.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] His three most famous speeches—the House Divided Speech, the Gettysburg Address, and his second inaugural address—all contain such quotes.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the 1840s, Lincoln subscribed to the Doctrine of Necessity, a belief that the human mind was controlled by a higher power.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the death of his son Edward in 1850, Lincoln more frequently expressed a dependence on God.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] He never joined a church, although he and his wife frequently attended First Presbyterian Church in Springfield, Illinois, beginning in 1852.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] While president, Lincoln often attended services at the New York Avenue Presbyterian Church in Washington, D.C.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] The death of his son Willie in February 1862 may have caused him to look toward religion for solace.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's frequent use of religious imagery and language toward the end of his life may have reflected his own personal beliefs or might have been a device to reach his audiences, who were mostly evangelical Protestants.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Sources differ in how they describe his religious beliefs.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephen Mansfield describes "an atheist or religiously skeptical Lincoln" as "the prevailing view", although he argues that "there was a spiritual journey of some kind in Abraham Lincoln's life".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Richard Carwardine writes that "Many elements of the inner Lincoln, including his personal faith ... necessarily remain a puzzle".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's last words were, as reported by his wife, "There is no place I so much desire to see as Jerusalem".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Michael Burlingame, Lincoln was described as "awkward" and "gawky" as a youth.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] In adolescence he was tall and strong, participating in jumping, throwing, wrestling, and footraces, and demonstrating exceptional strength.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Burlingame notes that Lincoln's clothes "were typically rough and suited to the frontier", with a gap between his shoes, socks, and pants that often exposed six or more inches of his shin; "he cared little about fashion".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln was a slender six feet four inches, with a high-pitched voice.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] While he is usually portrayed bearded, he did not grow a beard until 1860 at the suggestion of 11-year-old Grace Bedell; he was the first U.S. president to do so.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Herndon described Lincoln's face as "long, narrow, sallow, and cadaverous", his cheeks as "leathery and saffron-colored".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln described himself as having a "dark complexion, with coarse black hair".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although Lincoln's features were said to be "unpleasant to behold," Walt Whitman "wrote that Lincoln's face was 'so awful ugly it becomes beautiful.'" Lincoln's detractors also remarked on his appearance.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Among the illnesses that Lincoln is either documented or speculated to have suffered from are depression, smallpox, and malaria.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] He took blue mass pills, which contained mercury, to treat melancholy or hypochondriasis; this could have resulted in mercury poisoning.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] Several claims have been made that Lincoln's health was declining before his assassination, as photographs of Lincoln appear to show weight loss and facial changes.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p02] It has been proposed that he could have had a rare genetic disorder such as Marfan syndrome or multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2B.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] In surveys of U.S. scholars ranking presidents since 1948, the top three presidents are generally Lincoln, George Washington, and Franklin D.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] A 2004 study found that scholars in history and politics ranked Lincoln number one, while legal scholars placed him second after Washington.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] Kennedy, and Ronald Reagan were the top-ranked presidents in eight public opinion surveys by Gallup.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's assassination made him a national martyr.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] He was viewed by abolitionists as a champion of human liberty.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] Many, though not all, in the South considered Lincoln to be a man of outstanding ability.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] In the New Deal era, liberals honored Lincoln as an advocate of the common man who they claimed would have supported the welfare state, and Lincoln became a favorite of liberal intellectuals across the world.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] The high point came in 1922 with the dedication of the Lincoln Memorial on the National Mall in Washington, D.C.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Black orator and former slave Frederick Douglass stated that in "his company, I was never reminded of my humble origin, or of my unpopular color", and Lincoln has long been known as the Great Emancipator.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] By the late 1960s, some Black intellectuals denied that Lincoln deserved that title.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lerone Bennett Jr. won wide attention when he called Lincoln a White supremacist in 1968.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] He noted that Lincoln used ethnic slurs and argued that Lincoln opposed social equality and proposed that freed slaves voluntarily move to another country.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] Defenders of Lincoln highlighted his condemnation of slavery and his contributions to its abolition, casting his delays and racist rhetoric as concessions to political necessity rather than reflections of his personal beliefs.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has also been characterized as a folk hero and as "Honest Abe".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] David Herbert Donald opined in his 1996 biography that Lincoln was endowed with the personality trait of negative capability, attributed to extraordinary leaders who were "capable of being in uncertainties ... without any irritable reaching after fact and reason".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has often been portrayed by Hollywood, almost always in a flattering light; the film historian Melvyn Stokes writes that "moviemakers have commonly used Lincoln primarily as a metaphor for ideas and values they approved".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's portrait appears on two denominations of United States currency, the penny and the $5 bill.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] He appears on postage stamps across the world, including in Ghana, Honduras, China, Haiti, Nicaragua, Colombia, and Argentina.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] He has been memorialized in many town, city, and county names, including the capital of Nebraska.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] The United States Navy has named three vessels after Lincoln, including the *Nimitz*-class aircraft carrier USS *Abraham Lincoln* (CVN-72).
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Lincoln Memorial in Washington, D.C., is one of the most visited National Park Service sites in the country.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] Memorials in Springfield, Illinois, include the Abraham Lincoln Presidential Library and Museum, Lincoln's home, and his tomb.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] A carving of Lincoln appears with those of three other presidents on Mount Rushmore, which receives about 3 million visitors a year.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] A statue of Lincoln completed by Augustus Saint-Gaudens stands in Lincoln Park, Chicago, with recastings given as diplomatic gifts standing in Parliament Square, London, and Parque Lincoln, Mexico City.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] Several states commemorate "Presidents' Day" as "Washington–Lincoln Day".
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has been extensively portrayed in media.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] Early works, such as *Abraham Lincoln's Clemency* (1910), attempted to mythologize him, emphasizing his mercifulness.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] Works from the Great Depression era, such as *Young Mr.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln* (1939), embellished his early struggles and folksiness.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] The 1938 play *Abe Lincoln in Illinois* won a Pulitzer Prize and was adapted in film.
[src:ken-burns/abraham-lincoln-p03] After a marked decrease in film portrayals between 1941 and 1999, Daniel Day-Lewis won the Academy Award for Best Actor for his portrayal in *Lincoln*, a 2012 biographical film directed by Steven Spielberg.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The **Academy Awards**, more commonly known as the **Oscars**, are awards based on artistic and technical merit in film.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] They are presented annually by the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS) in the United States in recognition of excellence in cinematic achievements, as assessed by the Academy's voting membership.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The Oscars are widely considered to be the most prestigious awards in the American film industry, predominantly centered around films produced in Hollywood.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The major award categories, known as the **Academy Awards of Merit**, are presented during a live televised Hollywood ceremony in February or March.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] It is the longest running worldwide entertainment awards ceremony.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The 1st Academy Awards were held in 1929.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The second ceremony, in 1930, was the first to be broadcast by radio, and the 1953 ceremony was the first to be televised.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] It is the oldest of the four major annual American entertainment awards.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Its counterparts — the Emmy Awards for television, the Tony Awards for Broadway theatre, and the Grammy Awards for music — are modeled after the Academy Awards.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The Oscar statuette depicts a knight, rendered in the Art Deco style.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The first Academy Awards presentation was held on May 16, 1929 at a private dinner function at the Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel, with an audience of about 270 people.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The post-awards party was held at the Mayfair Hotel.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The cost of guest tickets for that night's ceremony was $5 (equivalent to $94 in 2025).
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Fifteen statuettes were awarded, honoring artists, directors, and other participants in the film-making industry of the time, for their works during the 1927–28 period.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] For this first ceremony, winners were announced to the media three months earlier.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] For the second ceremony in 1930, and the rest of the first decade, the results were given to newspapers for publication at 11:00 pm on the night of the awards.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In 1940, the *Los Angeles Times* announced the winners before the ceremony began.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] As a result, in 1941 the Academy started using a sealed envelope to reveal the names of the winners.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The term "Oscar" is a registered trademark of the AMPAS.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Historically, the Oscars had been the prime example of glamor in the United States; however, a movement away from both network television and award shows has led to the shift of the focus of glamor from the Oscars to the Met Gala.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The Oscars have suffered declining network television ratings and will be moving to YouTube in 2029.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The first Best Actor awarded was Emil Jannings, for his performances in *The Last Command* and *The Way of All Flesh*.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] As he had to return to Europe before the ceremony, the Academy agreed to give him the prize early, making him the first Academy Award recipient.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] For the first Awards, winners were recognized for multiple films during the qualifying period; Jannings received the award for two films in which he starred, and Janet Gaynor won the first Best Actress award for performances in three films.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Beginning with the second ceremony, performers received separate nominations for individual films; no performer has received multiple nominations in the same category since the 3rd Academy Awards.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] For the first five ceremonies, the eligibility period ran from August 1 to July 31.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Best Foreign Language Film, now known as Best International Feature Film, was introduced at the 20th Academy Awards as a special award, and became a competitive category at the 29th Academy Awards.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The 74th Academy Awards, held in 2002, presented the first Academy Award for Best Animated Feature, won by *Shrek*.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Since 1973, all Academy Awards ceremonies, except for 2021, have ended with the Academy Award for Best Picture.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Traditionally, the winners of the acting categories will present an award at the following year's ceremony.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The previous year's winners for Best Actor and Best Supporting Actor present the awards for Best Actress and Best Supporting Actress, respectively, and vice versa.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In 2009, this model was replaced by each acting award being introduced by five previous winners, each of whom introduces one of the nominated performances, referred to as the "Fab 5" presenters format.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The Fab 5 model returned in 2024 after a 15-year hiatus.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] On February 9, 2020, *Parasite* became the first foreign-language film to win Best Picture at the 92nd Academy Awards.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The 93rd Academy Awards ceremony, honoring the best films of 2020 and early 2021, was held on April 25, 2021, after it was postponed from its original February 28, 2021, schedule due to the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on cinema.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] As with the two previous ceremonies, there was no host.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] It took place at the Dolby Theatre in Los Angeles, California for the 19th consecutive year, with satellite locations at Union Station also in Los Angeles.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Because of the virus impact on films and TV industries, Academy president David Rubin and CEO Dawn Hudson announced that for the 2021 Oscar Ceremony, streaming films with a previously planned theatrical release were eligible.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The theatrical requirement was reinstated starting with the 95th Academy Awards.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The Oscar statuette, officially the Academy Award of Merit, is given to winners of each year's awards.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Made of gold-plated bronze on a black metal base, it is 13.5 in (34.3 cm) tall, weighs 8.5 lb (3.9 kg) and depicts a knight rendered in Art Deco style holding a sword standing on a reel of film with five spokes.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The five spokes represent the original branches of the Academy: Actors, Writers, Directors, Producers, and Technicians.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Sculptor George Stanley, who also did the Muse Fountain at the Hollywood Bowl, sculpted Cedric Gibbons' design.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The statuettes presented at the initial ceremonies were gold-plated solid bronze.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Within a few years, the bronze was abandoned in favor of Britannia metal, a pewter-like alloy that is then plated in copper, nickel silver, and finally, 24-karat gold.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Due to a metal shortage during World War II, Oscars were made of painted plaster for three years.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Following the war, the Academy invited recipients to redeem the plaster figures for gold-plated metal ones.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The only addition to the Oscar since it was created is a minor streamlining of the base.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The original Oscar mold was cast in 1928 at the C.W.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Shumway & Sons Foundry in Batavia, Illinois, which also contributed to casting the molds for the Vince Lombardi Trophy and Emmy Award statuettes.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] From 1972 to 1986, the Oscar statues were cast at the Dodge Trophy Company in Crystal Lake, Illinois.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] From 1987 to 2015, approximately 50 Oscars in a tin alloy with gold plating were made each year in Chicago by Illinois manufacturer R.S.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] It would take between three and four weeks to manufacture 50 statuettes.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In 2016, the Academy returned to bronze as the core metal of the statuettes, handing manufacturing duties to Walden, New York-based Polich Tallix Fine Art Foundry, now owned and operated by UAP Urban Art Projects.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] While based on a digital scan of an original 1929 Oscar, the statuettes retain their modern-era dimensions and black pedestal.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Cast in liquid bronze from 3D-printed ceramic molds and polished, they are then electroplated in 24-karat gold by Brooklyn, New York-based Epner Technology.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The time required to produce 50 such statuettes is roughly three months.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Owens is expected to continue producing other awards for the Academy, and service existing Oscars that need replating.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The origin of the nickname of the trophy has been disputed, as multiple people have taken credit for naming the trophy "Oscar".
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Margaret Herrick, librarian and president of the Academy, may have said she named it after her supposed uncle Oscar in 1931.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The only corroboration was a 1938 clipping from the *Los Angeles Examiner*, in which Herrick told a story of her and her husband joking with each other using the phrase, "How's your uncle Oscar".
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Bette Davis, in her 1962 autobiography, claimed she named it in 1936 after her first husband, Harmon Oscar Nelson, of whom the statue's rear end reminded her.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] But the term had been in use at least two years before.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] But in the newspaper clipping that Skolsky referred to, he wrote that "these statues are called 'Oscars'", meaning that the name was already in use.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In 2021, Brazilian researcher Waldemar Dalenogare Neto contradicted Skolsky's claim to have used the term first, finding the probable first public mention of the name "Oscar" in journalist Relman Morin's "Cinematters" column in the *Los Angeles Evening Record* on December 5, 1933.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Since the awards did not take place that year, he said: "What's happened to the annual Academy banquet?
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Bruce Davis, a former executive director of the Academy, credited Eleanore Lilleberg, a secretary at the Academy when the award was first introduced, for the nickname.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] She had overseen the pre-ceremony handling of the awards.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Davis credits Lilleberg because he found in an autobiography of Einar Lilleberg, Eleanore's brother, that Einar had referenced a Norwegian army veteran named Oscar whom the two knew in Chicago, whom Einar described as having always "stood straight and tall".
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] He asserts credit "should almost certainly belong to" Lilleberg.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] To prevent information identifying the Oscar winners from leaking ahead of the ceremony, Oscar statuettes presented at the ceremony have blank baseplates.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Until 2010, winners returned their statuettes to the Academy and had to wait several weeks to have their names inscribed on their respective Oscars.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Since 2010, winners have had the option of having engraved nameplates applied to their statuettes at an inscription-processing station at the Governor's Ball, a party held immediately after the Oscar ceremony.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Owens company has engraved nameplates made before the ceremony, bearing the name of every potential winner.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The nameplates for the non-winning nominees are later recycled.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Before 1950, Oscar statuettes were, and remain, the property of the recipient.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Since then the statuettes have been legally encumbered by the requirement that the statuette be first offered for sale back to the Academy for $1.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] If a winner refuses to agree to this stipulation, then the Academy keeps the statuette.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Academy Awards predating this agreement have been sold in public auctions and private deals for six-figure sums.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In 1989, Michael Todd's grandson tried to sell Todd's Best Picture Oscar for his 1956 production of *Around the World in 80 Days* to a movie prop collector.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The Academy earned enforcement of its statuette contract by gaining a permanent injunction against the sale.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In 1992, Harold Russell consigned his 1946 Oscar for Best Supporting Actor for *The Best Years of Our Lives* to auction to raise money for his wife's medical expenses.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Though his decision caused controversy, the first Oscar ever to be sold passed to a private collector on August 6, 1992, for $60,500 (equivalent to $138,804 in 2025).
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Russell defended his action, saying, "I don't know why anybody would be critical.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] My wife's health is much more important than sentimental reasons.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The movie will be here, even if Oscar isn't".
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In December 2011, Orson Welles' 1941 Oscar for *Citizen Kane* (Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay) was put up for auction, after his heirs won a 2004 court decision contending that Welles did not sign any agreement to return the statue to the Academy.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Some buyers have subsequently returned the statuettes to the Academy, which keeps them in its treasury.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The Academy also awards Nicholl Fellowships in Screenwriting.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] From 2004 to 2020, the Academy Award nomination results were announced to the public in mid-January.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Prior to that, the results were announced in early February.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In 2021, the nominees were announced in March.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In 2022, the nominees were announced in early February for the first time since 2003.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS), a professional honorary organization, is composed of 9,905 voting members as of 2024.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Academy membership is divided into different branches, with each representing a different discipline in film production.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] As of 2024, actors constitute the largest bloc, numbering 1,258 (12.7% of the voting body).
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Votes have been certified by the auditing firm PricewaterhouseCoopers, and its predecessor Price Waterhouse, since the 7th Academy Awards in 1935.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In May 2011, the Academy sent a letter advising its then-6,000 or so voting members that an online system for Oscar voting would be implemented in 2013, replacing mailed paper ballots.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] All AMPAS members must be invited to join by the Board of Governors, on behalf of Academy Branch Executive Committees.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Membership eligibility may be achieved by a competitive nomination, or an existing member may submit a name, based on other significant contributions to the field of motion pictures.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] New membership proposals are considered annually.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The Academy does not publicly disclose its membership, although as recently as 2007 press releases have announced the names of those who have been invited to join.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In 2012, the results of a study conducted by the *Los Angeles Times* were published describing the demographic breakdown of approximately 88% of AMPAS' voting membership.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Of the 5,100+ active voters confirmed, 94% were Caucasian, 77% were male, and 54% were found to be over the age of 60.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Thirty-three percent of voting members are former nominees (14%) and winners (19%).
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In 2016, the Academy launched an initiative to expand its membership and increase diversity.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In 2024, voting membership stood at 9,905.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In 2025, a newly announced procedure required Academy members to view all nominated films within a category to be eligible to cast a vote in the final round of that category.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The verification process will be done through the Academy's members-only streaming platform and submitting a form for films viewed at in-person events such as at festivals, screenings or private events.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The film must be shown at least three times on each day of its qualifying run, with at least one of the daily showings starting between 6 pm and 10 pm local time.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] For example, the 2009 Best Picture winner, *The Hurt Locker*, was originally first released in 2008, but did not qualify for the 2008 awards, as it did not play its Oscar-qualifying run in Los Angeles until mid-2009, thus qualifying for the 2009 awards.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Foreign films must include English subtitles.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Each country can submit only one film for consideration in the International Feature Film category per year.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Rule 2 states that a film must be feature-length, defined as a minimum of 40 minutes, except for short-subject awards.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] It must exist either on a 35 mm or 70 mm film print, or in 24 frame/s or 48 frame/s progressive scan digital cinema format, with a minimum projector resolution of 2,048 by 1,080 pixels.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Since the 90th Academy Awards, presented in 2018, multi-part and limited series have been ineligible for the Best Documentary Feature award.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] This followed the win of *O.J.: Made in America*, an eight-hour presentation that was screened in a limited release before being broadcast in five parts on ABC and ESPN, in that category in 2017.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The Academy's announcement of the new rule made no direct mention of that film.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The Best International Feature Film award does not require a U.S. release.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] It requires the film to be submitted as its country's official selection.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The qualifying theatrical runs must meet the same requirements as those for non-documentary films regarding numbers and times of screenings.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] A film must have been reviewed by a critic from *The New York Times*, *Time Out New York*, the *Los Angeles Times*, or *LA Weekly*.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Producers must submit an Official Screen Credits online form before the deadline.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] If it is not submitted by the defined deadline, the film will be ineligible for Academy Awards in any year.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The form includes the production credits for all related categories.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Awards in short film categories (Best Documentary Short Subject, Best Animated Short Film, and Best Live Action Short Film) have different eligibility rules from most other competitive awards.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] First, the qualifying period for release does not coincide with a calendar year, instead covering one year starting on October 1, and ending on September 30 of the calendar year before the ceremony.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Second, there are multiple methods of qualification.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The main method is a week-long theatrical release in *either* New York City *or* Los Angeles County during the eligibility period.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Films can also qualify by winning specified awards at one of several competitive film festivals designated by the Academy, also without regard to prior public distribution.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] A film that is selected as a gold, silver, or bronze medal winner in an appropriate category of the immediately previous Student Academy Awards is also eligible (Documentary category for that award, and Animation, Narrative, Alternative, or International for the other awards).
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The requirements for the qualifying theatrical run are also different from those for other awards.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] For the Documentary award, the screening must start between noon and 10 pm local time.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] For other awards, no specific start time is required, but the film must appear in regular theater listings with dates and screening times.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In late December, ballots and lists of eligible films are sent to the membership.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] For most categories, members from each of the branches vote to determine the nominees only in their respective categories, i.e. only directors vote for directors, writers for writers, actors for actors, etc.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In the special case of Best Picture, all voting members are eligible to select the nominees.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] A number of branches are only eligible to vote in Best Picture during nomination voting; this includes a producers' branch, as Best Picture is awarded to a film's producer(s), and other branches which have no corresponding award.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In all major categories, a variant of the single transferable vote is used, with each member casting a ballot with up to five nominees (ten for Best Picture) ranked preferentially.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In certain categories, including International Feature Film, Documentary and Animated Feature, nominees are selected by special screening committees made up of members from all branches.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In most categories, the winner is selected from among the nominees by plurality voting of all members.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Since 2009, the Best Picture winner has been chosen by instant-runoff voting.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Since 2013, re-weighted range voting has been used to select the nominees for the Best Visual Effects.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Film companies will spend as much as several million dollars on marketing to awards voters for a film in the running for Best Picture, in attempts to improve chances of receiving Oscars and other film awards conferred in Oscar season.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The Academy enforces rules to limit overt campaigning by its members to try to eliminate excesses and prevent the process from becoming undignified.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] It has an awards czar on staff who advises members on allowed practices and levies penalties on offenders.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] For example, a producer of the 2009 Best Picture nominee *The Hurt Locker* was disqualified as a producer in the category when he contacted associates urging them to vote for his film and not another that was seen as the front-runner.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] For the 99th Academy Awards (2027) and thereafter, AMPAS announced on May 1, 2026, its planned rules of eligibility.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Actors and scripts generated by artificial intelligence (AI) will be excluded from acting and screenwriting categories, but human actors rendered by AI will be reviewed at discretion.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Another rule change will expand eligibility of international films by allowing films that won eligible qualifying awards at film festivals, like the Palme d'Or (Cannes), the Golden Lion (Venice), and the Platform Prize (Toronto).
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Another new rule will allow an actor to be nominated more than once in a same acting category of the year.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Another rule change will clarify eligibility of the Best Original Song category: to be eligible, a first song played as the "first music cue" of the end credits must be heard in at least the film's last fifteen seconds until the end credits start.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The Academy Screening Room or Academy Digital Screening Room is a secure streaming platform which allows voting members of the Academy to view all eligible films in one place.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] It was introduced in 2019, for the 2020 Oscars.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] DVD screeners and Academy in-person screenings were still provided.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] For films to be included on the platform, the North American distributor must pay $12,500, including a watermarking fee, and a digital copy of the film to be prepared for streaming by the Academy.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The platform can be accessed via Apple TV and Roku players.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The watermarking process involved several video security firms, creating a forensic watermark and restricting the ability to take screenshots or screen recordings.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] In 2021, for the 2022 Oscars, the Academy banned all physical screeners and in-person screenings, restricting official membership viewing to the Academy Screening Room.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Films eligible in the Documentary and International categories were made available in different sections of the platform.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Distributors can also pay an extra fee to add video featurettes to promote their films on the platform.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The in-person screenings were cancelled because of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Eligible films do not have to be added to the platform, but the Academy advertises them to voting members when they are.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] The major awards are presented at a live televised ceremony, commonly in late February or early March following the relevant calendar year, and six weeks after the announcement of the nominees.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] It is the culmination of the film awards season, which usually begins during November or December of the previous year.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] This is an elaborate extravaganza, with the invited guests walking up the red carpet in the creations of the most prominent fashion designers of the day.
[src:ken-burns/academy-award-p01] Black tie dress is the most common outfit for men.
